{"title_page": "Exfoliation (cosmetology)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{medref|date=February 2013}}\n[[File:Skin.png|thumb|right|200 px|Cross-section of all skin layers.]]\n'''Exfoliation''' involves the removal of the oldest dead [[skin]] cells on the skin's outermost surface. Exfoliation is involved in all [[facial]]s, during [[microdermabrasion]] or [[chemical peels]]. Exfoliation can be achieved by mechanical or chemical means.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS205813+11-Jan-2008+BW20080111|title=New Skin - Via Exfoliation|work=Reuters|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nCredit is given to the ancient [[Egyptians]] for the practice of exfoliation.<ref name=\"Ray\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emedicine.com/DERM/topic533.htm|title=Medscape: Medscape Access|publisher=Emedicine.com|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref> In the [[Middle Ages]], wine was used as a chemical exfoliant, with [[tartaric acid]] as the active agent.<ref name=\"Ray\"/>  In [[Asia]], the practice of exfoliation started hundreds of years ago.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Positano|first1=Rock|title=Getting Under Your Skin|url=https://nypost.com/2007/09/18/getting-under-your-skin/|publisher=New York Post|accessdate=4 January 2015|date=18 September 2007}}</ref> The etymology of the word \"exfoliate\" comes from the Latin ''exfoliare'' (to strip off leaves).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/exfoliation|title=Exfoliation - Definition and More from the Free Merriam-Webster Dictionary|publisher=Merriam-webster.com|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Types==\nExfoliation is achieved either by mechanical or by chemical means.\n\n=== Mechanical ===\n[[File:Exfoliation tools.jpeg|thumb|Exfoliation methods used in Canada in 2011. Shown: top right, a bath sponge made of plastic mesh; lower right, a brush with a [[pumice]] stone on one side and a natural bristle brush on the other side, for foot exfoliation; lower left, a mud mask package for facial exfoliation; top left, a jar of perfumed body scrub to be used while bathing.]]\nThis process involves physically scrubbing the skin with an [[abrasive]].<ref name=\"Anitra\">{{cite web|url=http://spas.about.com/od/spatreatmentbasics/a/exfoliation.htm|title=What Is Exfoliation?|author=Anitra Brown|work=About|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref> Mechanical exfoliants include [[microfiber]] cloths, adhesive exfoliation sheets, [[Microbeads|micro-bead]] facial scrubs, crepe paper, crushed [[apricot kernel]] or [[almond]] shells, [[sugar]] or [[bath salts|salt crystals]], [[pumice]], and abrasive materials such as [[sponge]]s, [[loofah]]s, [[brush]]es, and simply fingernails.<ref name=\"Muniz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.askmen.com/fashion/fashiontip_200/248_fashion_advice.html|title=Exfoliation - AskMen|author=Alex Muniz|work=AskMen|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://altmedicine.about.com/od/homeremedyhowtos/a/dry_brushing.htm|title=How to Use a Dry Brush for Skin|author=Cathy Wong, ND|work=About|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref> Facial scrubs are available in [[Over-the-counter drug|over-the-counter products]] for application by the user. People with dry skin should avoid exfoliants which include a significant portion of pumice, or crushed volcanic rock. Pumice is considered a good material to exfoliate the skin of the feet. [[Microdermabrasion]] is another mechanical method of exfoliation.\n\n=== Chemical ===\nChemical exfoliants include scrubs containing [[salicylic acid]], [[glycolic acid]], fruit [[enzyme]]s, [[citric acid]], or [[malic acid]] which may be applied in high concentrations by a medical professional, or in lower concentrations in over-the-counter products. Chemical exfoliation may involve the use of products that contain [[alpha hydroxy acid]]s (AHAs), [[beta hydroxy acid]]s (BHAs), or enzymes that act to loosen the glue-like substance that holds the cells together, allowing them to ease away. This type of exfoliation is recommended for people treating [[acne]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wdxcyber.com/exfoliation.html|title=Beauty & Skin: Facial Skin Exfoliation|publisher=Wdxcyber.com|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref>  In beauty spa treatment in continental Europe, the chemical properties of wine-producing grapes are exploited in the practice of [[vinotherapy]] which is becoming increasingly popular.{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}}\n\n=== With hair removal ===\nSome methods of [[hair removal]] also exfoliate the skin.\n*[[Waxing]] is a mechanical process performed with the intention of plucking the hair, but it also functions as a mechanical exfoliant. It can be done every two to eight weeks. It is not carried out as frequently as many exfoliate. So, it does not fully substitute for an exfoliation regimen, but may substitute for a normal session in a regimen.\n*[[Nair (hair removal)|Nair]] is an example of a [[Chemical depilatory|chemical hair removal]] product which also functions as a chemical exfoliant. It is applied more frequently than waxing (once a week rather than once a month) since it only partially destroys hair below the skin, rather than destroying the entire root as with waxing. Using it weekly can substitute for a weekly exfoliant regime. It is a very aggressive chemical and cannot be used on the face, so other exfoliants would need to be used on the face.\n*[[Shaving|Wetshaving]] also has exfoliating properties: first, the action of moving a shaving brush vigorously across the face washes the face and removes dead skin at the same time. After applying the lather with a brush, the use of a double-edged safety razor or straight razor removes dead skin simply because the razor is dragged much more closely across the skin, and removes dead skin more effectively than a cartridge or electric razor.\n\n====Dermaplaning====\nDermaplaning is a medical procedure that exfoliates the skin (or [[epidermis]]) by [./Https://jasclairskincare.com/blogs/dermaplaning/the-benefits-of-dermaplaning removing dead skin and vellus hair] (peach fuzz). The procedure is performed by an aesthetician, who will gently glide a [[scalpel]] across the skin, removing the outermost layer of skin cells and hair from the face. As a byproduct, it also shaves off the vellus hair, but the hair will grow back at the same rate and texture as before, because it does not change the DNA of the hair bulb.<ref>Crawley, Kristen. [http://www.elle.com/beauty/hair/news/a37596/dermaplaning-facial-hair-removal/ \"Everything You Need to Know about Dermaplaning\"], ''[[Elle Magazine]]'', 7 July 2016. Retrieved on 16 May 2017.</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=December 2017}}<ref>Durland, Samantha. [https://www.realself.com/question/what-dermaplaning \"What is Dermaplaning\"], ''Real Self Magazine'', 12 December 2016. Retrieved on 16 May 2017.</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=December 2017}} The procedure involves the use of a 25-centimetre (10 in) scalpel which curves into a sharp point. In most cases, the blade is used on clean dry skin on the forehead, cheeks, chin, nose and neck. [https://jasclairskincare.com/blogs/dermaplaning/7-steps-to-dermaplaning-at-home Dermaplaning] can also be performed on skin that has had oil applied to it.\n\n==Promotion==\nIn popular media, exfoliants are advertised as treatments which promote beauty, youthful appearance, or health.<ref name=\"Muniz\"/>{{or|date=June 2014}}\n\n==Disadvantages==\nOne disadvantage to exfoliation is the high price of some of the products and methods used to achieve it. Exfoliation will lead to some initial redness to the skin. Near the end of chemical peels, the skin will frost, with colors varying from a bright white to grey on the skin surface.<ref name=\"Ray\"/> Over-exfoliation can easily leave the skin dry and irritated which is why it is advisable to not exfoliate more than twice a week.\n\n=== Marine environmental impact of microbeads ===\n{{See Also|Microbeads#Environmental_effects}}\n[[Microbead]] particles used in mechanical exfoliation are too small (less than 1 mm) to be caught by [[sewage works]], so tonnes of microbeads are released into the environment, which damages marine [[ecosystem]]s.<ref name=ns_23June2014>{{cite news |last1=Hitchings|first1=Lauren |date=23 June 2014 |title=Why Illinois has banned exfoliating face washes |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn25773-why-illinois-has-banned-exfoliating-face-washes.html#.U6mzeLHww5K |website=[[New Scientist]] |accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref> Consequently, in June 2014 the US state of [[Illinois]] became the first to ban the use of microbeads, and cosmetics manufacturers such as [[L'Oreal]], [[Johnson & Johnson]], and [[Colgate-Palmolive|Colgate]] agreed to use more natural ingredients.<ref name=ns_23June2014/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chemical peel]]\n* [[Debridement]]\n* [[Medical spa]]\n* [[Microdermabrasion]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Exfoliation (Cosmetology)}}\n[[Category:Skin care]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{medref|date=February 2013}}\n[[File:Skin.png|thumb|right|200 px|Cross-section of all skin layers.]]\n'''Exfoliation''' involves the removal of the oldest dead [[skin]] cells on the skin's outermost surface. Exfoliation is involved in all [[facial]]s, during [[microdermabrasion]] or [[chemical peels]]. Exfoliation can be achieved by mechanical or chemical means.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS205813+11-Jan-2008+BW20080111|title=New Skin - Via Exfoliation|work=Reuters|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nCredit is given to the ancient [[Egyptians]] for the practice of exfoliation.<ref name=\"Ray\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emedicine.com/DERM/topic533.htm|title=Medscape: Medscape Access|publisher=Emedicine.com|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref> In the [[Middle Ages]], wine was used as a chemical exfoliant, with [[tartaric acid]] as the active agent.<ref name=\"Ray\"/>  In [[Asia]], the practice of exfoliation started hundreds of years ago.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Positano|first1=Rock|title=Getting Under Your Skin|url=https://nypost.com/2007/09/18/getting-under-your-skin/|publisher=New York Post|accessdate=4 January 2015|date=18 September 2007}}</ref> The etymology of the word \"exfoliate\" comes from the Latin ''exfoliare'' (to strip off leaves).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/exfoliation|title=Exfoliation - Definition and More from the Free Merriam-Webster Dictionary|publisher=Merriam-webster.com|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Types==\nExfoliation is achieved either by mechanical or by chemical means.\n\n=== Mechanical ===\n[[File:Exfoliation tools.jpeg|thumb|Exfoliation methods used in Canada in 2011. Shown: top right, a bath sponge made of plastic mesh; lower right, a brush with a [[pumice]] stone on one side and a natural bristle brush on the other side, for foot exfoliation; lower left, a mud mask package for facial exfoliation; top left, a jar of perfumed body scrub to be used while bathing.]]\nThis process involves physically scrubbing the skin with an [[abrasive]].<ref name=\"Anitra\">{{cite web|url=http://spas.about.com/od/spatreatmentbasics/a/exfoliation.htm|title=What Is Exfoliation?|author=Anitra Brown|work=About|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref> Mechanical exfoliants include [[microfiber]] cloths, adhesive exfoliation sheets, [[Microbeads|micro-bead]] facial scrubs, crepe paper, crushed [[apricot kernel]] or [[almond]] shells, [[sugar]] or [[bath salts|salt crystals]], [[pumice]], and abrasive materials such as [[sponge]]s, [[loofah]]s, [[brush]]es, and simply fingernails.<ref name=\"Muniz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.askmen.com/fashion/fashiontip_200/248_fashion_advice.html|title=Exfoliation - AskMen|author=Alex Muniz|work=AskMen|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://altmedicine.about.com/od/homeremedyhowtos/a/dry_brushing.htm|title=How to Use a Dry Brush for Skin|author=Cathy Wong, ND|work=About|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref> Facial scrubs are available in [[Over-the-counter drug|over-the-counter products]] for application by the user. People with dry skin should avoid exfoliants which include a significant portion of pumice, or crushed volcanic rock. Pumice is considered a good material to exfoliate the skin of the feet. [[Microdermabrasion]] is another mechanical method of exfoliation.\n\n=== Chemical ===\nChemical exfoliants include scrubs containing [[salicylic acid]], [[glycolic acid]], fruit [[enzyme]]s, [[citric acid]], or [[malic acid]] which may be applied in high concentrations by a medical professional, or in lower concentrations in over-the-counter products. Chemical exfoliation may involve the use of products that contain [[alpha hydroxy acid]]s (AHAs), [[beta hydroxy acid]]s (BHAs), or enzymes that act to loosen the glue-like substance that holds the cells together, allowing them to ease away. This type of exfoliation is recommended for people treating [[acne]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wdxcyber.com/exfoliation.html|title=Beauty & Skin: Facial Skin Exfoliation|publisher=Wdxcyber.com|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref>  In beauty spa treatment in continental Europe, the chemical properties of wine-producing grapes are exploited in the practice of [[vinotherapy]] which is becoming increasingly popular.{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}}\n\n=== With hair removal ===\nSome methods of [[hair removal]] also exfoliate the skin.\n*[[Waxing]] is a mechanical process performed with the intention of plucking the hair, but it also functions as a mechanical exfoliant. It can be done every two to eight weeks. It is not carried out as frequently as many exfoliate. So, it does not fully substitute for an exfoliation regimen, but may substitute for a normal session in a regimen.\n*[[Nair (hair removal)|Nair]] is an example of a [[Chemical depilatory|chemical hair removal]] product which also functions as a chemical exfoliant. It is applied more frequently than waxing (once a week rather than once a month) since it only partially destroys hair below the skin, rather than destroying the entire root as with waxing. Using it weekly can substitute for a weekly exfoliant regime. It is a very aggressive chemical and cannot be used on the face, so other exfoliants would need to be used on the face.\n*[[Shaving|Wetshaving]] also has exfoliating properties: first, the action of moving a shaving brush vigorously across the face washes the face and removes dead skin at the same time. After applying the lather with a brush, the use of a double-edged safety razor or straight razor removes dead skin simply because the razor is dragged much more closely across the skin, and removes dead skin more effectively than a cartridge or electric razor.\n\n====Dermaplaning====\nDermaplaning is a medical procedure that exfoliates the skin (or [[epidermis]]) by removing dead skin and vellus hair (peach fuzz). The procedure is performed by an aesthetician, who will gently glide a [[scalpel]] across the skin, removing the outermost layer of skin cells and hair from the face. As a byproduct, it also shaves off the vellus hair, but the hair will grow back at the same rate and texture as before, because it does not change the DNA of the hair bulb.<ref>Crawley, Kristen. [http://www.elle.com/beauty/hair/news/a37596/dermaplaning-facial-hair-removal/ \"Everything You Need to Know about Dermaplaning\"], ''[[Elle Magazine]]'', 7 July 2016. Retrieved on 16 May 2017.</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=December 2017}}<ref>Durland, Samantha. [https://www.realself.com/question/what-dermaplaning \"What is Dermaplaning\"], ''Real Self Magazine'', 12 December 2016. Retrieved on 16 May 2017.</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=December 2017}} The procedure involves the use of a 25-centimetre (10 in) scalpel which curves into a sharp point. In most cases, the blade is used on clean dry skin on the forehead, cheeks, chin, nose and neck. Dermaplaning can also be performed on skin that has had oil applied to it.\n\n==Promotion==\nIn popular media, exfoliants are advertised as treatments which promote beauty, youthful appearance, or health.<ref name=\"Muniz\"/>{{or|date=June 2014}}\n\n==Disadvantages==\nOne disadvantage to exfoliation is the high price of some of the products and methods used to achieve it. Exfoliation will lead to some initial redness to the skin. Near the end of chemical peels, the skin will frost, with colors varying from a bright white to grey on the skin surface.<ref name=\"Ray\"/> Over-exfoliation can easily leave the skin dry and irritated which is why it is advisable to not exfoliate more than twice a week.\n\n=== Marine environmental impact of microbeads ===\n{{See Also|Microbeads#Environmental_effects}}\n[[Microbead]] particles used in mechanical exfoliation are too small (less than 1 mm) to be caught by [[sewage works]], so tonnes of microbeads are released into the environment, which damages marine [[ecosystem]]s.<ref name=ns_23June2014>{{cite news |last1=Hitchings|first1=Lauren |date=23 June 2014 |title=Why Illinois has banned exfoliating face washes |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn25773-why-illinois-has-banned-exfoliating-face-washes.html#.U6mzeLHww5K |website=[[New Scientist]] |accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref> Consequently, in June 2014 the US state of [[Illinois]] became the first to ban the use of microbeads, and cosmetics manufacturers such as [[L'Oreal]], [[Johnson & Johnson]], and [[Colgate-Palmolive|Colgate]] agreed to use more natural ingredients.<ref name=ns_23June2014/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chemical peel]]\n* [[Debridement]]\n* [[Medical spa]]\n* [[Microdermabrasion]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Exfoliation (Cosmetology)}}\n[[Category:Skin care]]\n", "name_user": "Jasclair", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eDermaplaning)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exfoliation_(cosmetology)"}
{"title_page": "Vicksburg Union order of battle", "text_new": "The following [[Union Army]] units and commanders fought in the [[Siege of Vicksburg]] of the [[American Civil War]]. The [[Vicksburg Confederate order of battle|Confederate order of battle]] is listed separately. Order of battle compiled from the army organization<ref>Multiple commander names indicate command succession of command during the battle or the campaign.</ref> during the campaign.<ref>Official Records, Series I, Volume XXIV, Part 2, [http://ebooks.library.cornell.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=moawar&cc=moawar&idno=waro0037&node=waro0037%3A1&view=image&seq=150&size=100 pages 148-158]</ref> \n\n==Abbreviations used==\n===Military rank===\n* '''MG''' = [[Major general (United States)|Major General]]\n* '''BG''' = [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]\n* '''Col''' = [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]\n* '''Ltc''' = [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]]\n* '''Maj''' = [[Major (United States)|Major]]\n* '''Cpt''' = [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]\n* '''Lt''' = [[1st_Lieutenant#U.S._Army.2C_U.S._Marine_Corps_and_U.S._Air_Force|Lieutenant]]\n* '''Sgt''' = [[Sergeant#American Civil War|Sergeant]]\n\n===Other===\n* '''w''' = [[Wounded in action|wounded]]\n* '''mw''' = [[Mortal wound|mortally wounded]]\n* '''k''' = [[Killed in action|killed]]\n\n==[[Army of the Tennessee]]==\nMG [[Ulysses S. Grant]], Commanding<br>\n<br>\n'''General Staff''':\n* Acting Inspector General: BG [[Jeremiah C. Sullivan]]\n* Chief of Transportation: Col [[Joseph D. Webster]]\n* Chief of Staff: Ltc [[John A. Rawlins]]\n\n'''General Headquarters''':\n* Escort: 4th Illinois Cavalry, Company A: Cpt Embury D. Osband\n* Engineers: [[Bissell's Engineer Regiment of the West|1st Battalion, Engineer Regiment of the West]]: Maj William Tweeddale\n* [[Mississippi Marine Brigade]]: BG [[Alfred W. Ellet]]<ref>[http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/05/17/the-mississippi-marine-brigade/ The judge advocate general declared this unit as a special contingent of the army, however Grant later wrote \"the Marine Brigade is not subject to my orders\"]</ref>\n** [[United States Ram Fleet|Mississippi Ram Fleet]]: Col [[Charles Rivers Ellet]]\n** 1st Battalion Infantry: Ltc George E. Currie\n** 1st Battalion Cavalry: Major James M. Hubbard\n** Artillery Battery: Cpt Daniel Walling\n\n<br />\n===[[IX Corps (Union Army)|IX Corps]]===\nMG [[John Parke]]<ref>IX Corps: joined from the Department of the Ohio, June 14 to 17.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=32% | Division\n! width=32% | Brigade\n! Regiments and Others\n|-\n| rowspan=3 |\nFirst Division\n\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\nBG [[Thomas Welsh (general)|Thomas Welsh]]\n| 1st Brigade\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCol Henry Bowman\n|\n* [[36th Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry|36th Massachusetts]]: Ltc John B. Norton\n* [[17th Michigan Volunteer Infantry Regiment|17th Michigan]]: Ltc Constant Luce\n* [[27th Michigan Volunteer Infantry Regiment|27th Michigan]]: Col Dorus M. Fox\n* [[45th Pennsylvania Infantry|45th Pennsylvania]]: Col [[John I. Curtin]]\n|-\n| 3rd Brigade\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCol [[Daniel Leasure]]\n|\n* [[2nd Michigan Volunteer Infantry Regiment|2nd Michigan]]: Col William Humphrey\n* [[8th Michigan Volunteer Infantry Regiment|8th Michigan]]: Col Frank Graves\n* [[20th Michigan Volunteer Infantry Regiment|20th Michigan]]: Ltc W. Huntington Smith\n* [[79th New York Volunteer Infantry|79th New York]]: Col David Morrison\n* [[100th Pennsylvania Infantry|100th Pennsylvania]]: Ltc Mathew M. Dawson\n|-\n| Artillery\n|\n* [[Independent Battery D, Pennsylvania Light Artillery|Battery D, Pennsylvania Light]]: Cpt George W. Durell<ref>Transferred from Second Division June 25.</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=4 |\nSecond Division\n\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\nBG [[Robert B. Potter]]\n| 1st Brigade\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCol [[Simon Goodell Griffin]]\n|\n* [[6th New Hampshire Volunteer Infantry|6th New Hampshire]]: Ltc Henry 