omer]] ('''k''') [May 22]\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCol Holden Putnam<ref>Assumed command May 22.</ref>\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;\nBG Charles L. Matthies<ref>Assumed command June 2.</ref>\n|\n* [[93rd Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment|93rd Illinois]]: Col Holden Putnam, Ltc Nicholas C. Buswell, Col Holden Putnam\n* [[5th Iowa Volunteer Infantry Regiment|5th Iowa]]: Ltc [[Ezekiel S. Sampson]], Col Jabez Banbury\n* [[10th Iowa Volunteer Infantry Regiment|10th Iowa]]: Col William E. Small\n* [[26th Missouri Volunteer Infantry|26th Missouri]]: Maj Charles F. Brown ('''k''') [May 16]; Cpt Benjamin D. Dean\n|-\n| Artillery.\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCpt Frank C. Sands\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCpt Henry Dillon<ref>Assumed command June 6.</ref>\n|\n* Battery M, 1st Missouri Light: Lt Julius W. MacMurray\n* [[11th Ohio Battery|11th Battery, Ohio Light]]:<ref>Temporarily attached to Kimball's Division, XVI Corps, June 6.</ref> Lt Fletcher E. Armstrong\n* [[6th Independent Battery Wisconsin Light Artillery|6th Battery, Wisconsin Light]]: Cpt Henry Dillon, Lt Samuel F. Clark\n* [[12th Independent Battery Wisconsin Light Artillery|12th Battery, Wisconsin Light]]: Cpt William Zickerick\n|-\n| rowspan=2 |\nHerron's Division<ref>Joined from the Department of the Missouri June 11.</ref>\n\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\nMG [[Francis J. Herron]]\n| 1st Brigade\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;\nBG [[William Vandever]]\n|\n* [[37th Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment|37th Illinois]]: Col [[John C. Black]]\n* [[26th Indiana Infantry Regiment|26th Indiana]]: Col John G. Clark\n* [[20th Iowa Volunteer Infantry Regiment|20th Iowa]]: Col [[William McEntyre Dye]]\n* [[34th Iowa Volunteer Infantry Regiment|34th Iowa]]: Col [[George Washington Clark|George W. Clark]]\n* [[38th Iowa Volunteer Infantry Regiment|38th Iowa]]: Col D. Henry Hughes\n* Battery E, 1st Missouri Light Artillery: Cpt Nelson Cole\n* Battery F, 1st Missouri Light Artillery: Cpt Joseph Foust\n|-\n| 2nd Brigade\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;\nBG [[William W. Orme]]\n|\n* [[94th Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment|94th Illinois]]: Col [[John McNulta]]\n* [[19th Iowa Volunteer Infantry Regiment|19th Iowa]]: Ltc Daniel Kent\n* [[20th Wisconsin Volunteer Infantry Regiment|20th Wisconsin]]: Col [[Henry Bertram]]\n* Battery B, 1st Missouri Light Artillery: Cpt Martin Welfley\n|-\n|\n| Unattached cavalry\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCol [[Cyrus Bussey]]\n|\n* [[5th Regiment Illinois Volunteer Cavalry|5th Illinois Cavalry]]: Maj Thomas A. Apperson\n* [[3rd Regiment Iowa Volunteer Cavalry|3rd Iowa Cavalry]]: Maj Oliver H. P. Scott\n* [[2nd Regiment Wisconsin Volunteer Cavalry|2nd Wisconsin Cavalry]]: Col Thomas Stephens\n|}\n\n===District of Northeast Louisiana===\nBG [[Elias Smith Dennis|Elias S. Dennis]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=33% | '''Brigades'''\n! '''Regiments and batteries'''\n|-\n| Detached Brigade\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCol George W. Neeley\n|\n* [[63rd Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment|63rd Illinois]]: Col Joseph B. McCown\n* [[108th Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment|108th Illinois]]: Ltc Charles Turner\n* [[120th Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment|120th Illinois]]: Col George W. McKeaig\n* [[131st Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment|131st Illinois]]: Col George W. Neeley, Maj Joseph L. Purvis\n* [[10th Illinois Volunteer Cavalry Regiment|10th Illinois Cavalry]], Companies A, D, G, and K: Maj Elvis P. Shaw\n|-\n| African Brigade\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCol [[Isaac F. Shephard]]\n|\n* [[8th Louisiana Regiment Infantry (African Descent)|8th Louisiana]]: Col [[Hiram Scofield]] (also commanded Post of Milliken's Bend, La)\n* [[9th Louisiana Regiment Infantry (African Descent)|9th Louisiana]]: Col [[Hermann Lieb]], Maj Erastus N. Owen, Ltc Charles L. Page\n* [[11th Louisiana Regiment Infantry (African Descent)|11th Louisiana]]: Col Edwin W. Chamberlain, Ltc Cyrus Sears\n* [[13th Louisiana Regiment Infantry (African Descent)|13th Louisiana]]: Lt H. Knoll\n* [[51st United States Colored Infantry Regiment|1st Mississippi]]: Ltc A. Watson Webber\n* [[53rd United States Colored Infantry Regiment|3rd Mississippi]]: Col Richard H. Ballinger\n|-\n| Post of Goodrich's Landing, La.\n<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCol William F. Wood\n|\n* [[1st Arkansas Infantry Regiment (Union)|1st Arkansas]]: Ltc James W. Campbell\n* [[10th Louisiana Regiment Infantry (African Descent)|10th Louisiana]]: Ltc Frederick M. Crandall\n|}\n\n<br />\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n*U.S. War Department, [http://cdl.library.cornell.edu/moa/browse.monographs/waro.html ''The War of the Rebellion'']: ''a Compilation of the [[Official Records of the American Civil War|Official Records]] of the Union and Confederate Armies'', U.S. Government Printing Office, 1880&ndash;1901.\n*U.S. War Department, ''The War of the Rebellion: a Compilation of the Official Records of the Union and Confederate Armies'', U.S. Government Printing Office, 1880&ndash;1901:  [http://ebooks.library.cornell.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=moawar&cc=moawar&idno=waro0037&node=waro0037%3A1&view=image&seq=169&size=100 General summary of Casualties in the Union forces against Vicksburg, May 1&ndash;July 4, 1863.]\n*[http://www.civilwarhome.com/vicksburgorgunion.htm Civil War Home: Organization of the Union Army At Vicksburg May 19&ndash;July 4, 1863 -- The Siege of Vicksburg, Miss. ]\n*[http://www.nps.gov/vick/historyculture/order-of-battle-union.htm National Park Service: Vicksburg National Military Park (Siege of Vicksburg: Union order of battle).]\n*[http://www.nps.gov/vick/historyculture/copy-of-troops-in-the-campaign-siege-and-defense-of-vicksburg.htm National Park Service: Vicksburg National Military Park (Troops in the Campaign, Siege and Defense of Vicksburg).]\n*[http://www.nps.gov/vick/historyculture/upload/Sum%20of%20Casualties.pdf National Park Service: Vicksburg National Military Park (Campaign, Siege and Defense of Vicksburg -- General summary of Casualties, March 29&ndash;July 4).]\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vicksburg Union Order Of Battle}}\n[[Category:American Civil War orders of battle]]\n", "name_user": "Djmaschek", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eXVI Corps (detachment):Add link: Cogswell's Battery.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vicksburg_Union_order_of_battle"}
{"title_page": "Mark Aubry", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Mark Aubry\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1954|11|24}}\n| birth_place  = [[Noranda, Quebec]], Canada\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  = \n| alma_mater   = [[University of Ottawa]]\n| occupation   = [[Physician]]\n| years_active = 1981\u2013present \n| employer     = [[Ottawa Senators]] \n| known_for    = [[Sports medicine]] specialist, and [[Chief Medical Officer]] of the [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] and [[Hockey Canada]]\n| awards       = [[Paul Loicq Award]], Dr. [[Tom Pashby]] sports safety award \n}}\n\n'''Mark John Aubry''' (born November 24, 1954) is a Canadian [[physician]] and [[sports medicine]] specialist. He is the team physician for the [[Ottawa Senators]], and serves as the [[Chief Medical Officer]] of both the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]], and [[Hockey Canada]]. He researches and lectures on [[concussion]]s, plays a leadership role for safety in sport, and is an injury prevention activist in minor ice hockey. He is a recipient of the [[Paul Loicq Award]] for his international work, and the Dr. [[Tom Pashby]] sports safety award for Canada.\n\n==Early life==\nAubry was born November 24, 1954, in [[Noranda, Quebec]],<ref name=\"IIHF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iihf.com/home-of-hockey/news/iihf-hof-2014/|title=Paul Loicq Award: Dr Mark Aubry (CAN)|date=2014|website=IIHF|access-date=July 31, 2018}}</ref> and learned to speak both English and French.<ref name=\"cpso\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cpso.on.ca/DoctorDetails/Aubry-Mark-John/0028044-32867|title=Aubry, Mark John (CPSO#: 32867)|website=[[College of Physicians and Surgeons of Ontario]]|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> He attended [[Merivale High School]], and played hockey, football and baseball at school.<ref name=\"MayorsCup\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insideottawavalley.com/community-story/3803201-fury-s-zito-picked-for-top-male-coach-award/|title=Fury's Zito picked for top male coach award|date=January 21, 2011|website=InsideOttawaValley.com|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> Aubry began playing [[junior ice hockey]] as a [[Centre (ice hockey)|centreman]]; he is listed at 6 feet tall, and 180 pounds, for the [[Rockland Nationals|Ottawa M and W Rangers]] in the [[Central Canada Hockey League]] during the 1971\u201372 season.<ref name=\"hockeydb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=72733|title=Mark Aubry hockey statistics and profile|website=hockeydb|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> During the 1972\u201373 season, he was coached by future [[IIHF Hall of Fame]] inductee, [[Derek Holmes (ice hockey)|Derek Holmes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/leagues/seasons/teams/0032181973.html|title=Ottawa M and W Rangers 1972&ndash;73 roster and scoring statistics|website=hockeydb.com|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> Aubry won the most valuable player award and the sportsmanship award in the 1972\u201373 season with the Rangers, and won the sportsmanship award again in the 1973\u201374 season.<ref name=\"CCHL\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thecchl.ca/season-award-archives|title=Season Award Archives|website=Central Canada Hockey League|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> He then played for the [[Ottawa Gee-Gees]] during the 1974&ndash;75 and 1975&ndash;76 seasons,<ref name=\"hockeydb\" /><ref name=\"uottawa\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uottawa.ca/archives/sites/www.uottawa.ca.archives/files/hockey.pdf|title=Historique du hockey \u00e0 l'Universit\u00e9 d'Ottawa|language=french|website=University of Ottawa archives|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> while earning his medical degree.<ref name=\"dr-aubry\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeycanada.ca/en-ca/exclusive/quebec-hockey-summit/home/attendees/speakers/mark-aubry|title=Doctor Mark Aubry|website=Hockey Canada|access-date=July 31, 2018}}</ref> After playing, he worked as a trainer for the Gee-Gees.<ref name=\"MayorsCup\" />\n\n==Medical career==\nAubry graduated from the [[University of Ottawa]] in 1978.<ref name=\"cpso\" /> He established a [[family medicine]] office in [[Hull, Quebec]] on September, 18, 1981.<ref name=\"cpso\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> As of 2018, he is a director at the Ottawa Sport Medicine Centre,<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> and is a team physician for the [[Ottawa Senators]].<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/senators/team/front-office#medical-staff|title=Hockey Operations|website=Ottawa Senators|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> Aubry previously served as the team physician for the [[Ottawa 67's]] from 1996 to 2005,<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> the [[Ottawa Rough Riders]],<ref name=\"MayorsCup\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> the [[Ottawa Renegades]],<ref name=\"Renegades\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/opening-day-of-renegades-training-camp-highlighted-by-medicals-meetings-and-preparation/n-3168889|title=Opening day of Renegades training camp highlighted by medicals, meetings and preparation|date=May 28, 2005|website=OurSports Central|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> and the [[Ottawa Lynx]].<ref name=\"Pashby\" /> He was a trainer on [[minor ice hockey]] teams from 1989 to 2000, [[Chief Medical Officer]] (CMO) for the Canadian team at the [[1991 Winter Universiade]], and CMO of [[Canada at the 1992 Winter Olympics]] in [[Albertville]].<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" />\n\n===Sports medicine===\nAubry has spent significant time working in [[sports medicine]], lecturing on injury prevention, and researching [[concussion]]s and [[spinal cord]] injuries with respect to [[Checking (ice hockey)|body checking]] in ice hockey.<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /><ref name=\"Pashby\" /><ref name=\"bodycheck\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeyeasternontario.ca/docs/HC_Body_Checking_Brief_1.pdf|title=Hockey Canada\u2014Body Checking Brief|date=April 17, 2013|website=Hockey Eastern Ontario|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He helped organize three symposiums on sports concussions (2001 in [[Vienna]], 2004 in [[Prague]], and 2008 in [[Z\u00fcrich]]), to assist doctors in identifying and treating concussions.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> Aubry was one of the physicians consulted for the 2011 report ''Brain Injury Guide for Youth'',<ref name=\"Kutcher\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ontarioshores.ca/UserFiles/Servers/Server_6/File/PDFs/bi_teen_guide_4.pdf|title=Brain Injury Guide for Youth|last=Kutcher|first=Stan|date=2011|page=3|website=Ontario Shores|publisher=Teenmentalhealth.org|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> and was one of the medical experts that helped write the module ''Making Head Way in Sport'' released in 2014, for the Coaching Association of Canada to educate on when it is okay to return to play.<ref name=\"CAC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.coach.ca/making-head-way-in-sport-elearning-module-is-now-available-at-no-charge-p156794|title=Making Head Way in Sport eLearning module is now available at no charge|date=July 17, 2014|website=Coaching Association of Canada|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> Aubry has also spoken against focusing too much on one sport at a young age, as it has not only \"taken the fun out of it\", but also has physical and cultural risks in not developing the person.<ref name=\"Scanlan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/ottawa-citizen/20170322/281479276237544|title=Can sports be fun again?|last=Scanlan|first=Wayne|date=March 22, 2017|website=PressReader.com|publisher=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|title=World Hockey Summit|quote=\"We're exposing these kids to an increased risk of injury at an age where I think we should still be talking about skill development and having fun\".|source=&mdash;''Mark Aubry'', 2010<ref name=\"Fitz-Gerald\" /><ref name=\"TheHockeyNews\" /><ref name=\"sportsnet\" />|width=27.5%|align=right}}\n\nAt the 2010 [[World Hockey Summit]], a joint project hosted by the National Hockey League, the [[National Hockey League Players' Association]], Hockey Canada, [[USA Hockey]], the IIHF, and the [[Canadian Hockey League]],<ref name=\"NHLPA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nhlpa.com/news/1-13651/whos-who-of-hockey-to-gather-for-world-hockey-summit|title=Who's Who of Hockey To Gather for World Hockey Summit|date=July 29, 2010|website=National Hockey League Players Association|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> Aubry called for raising the minimum age for body checking to 13 or 14 and eliminating hits from behind altogether.<ref name=\"Fitz-Gerald\" /><ref name=\"TheHockeyNews\" /> Based on his research and experience, he argued that children should be developing skills instead, as they are the most vulnerable to injury due to height and weight differences; he cited research which highlights risks of long-term effects for athletes who have had multiple concussions, specifically younger hockey players.<ref name=\"Fitz-Gerald\">{{cite news|title=Delay body checks till 13, 14, doc says|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|last1=Fitz-Gerald|first1=Sean|last2=Strong|first2=Gregory|date=August 25, 2010|page=24|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-25-2010-776136/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref name=\"TheHockeyNews\">{{cite web|url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/medical-doctor-nhl-coach-say-kids-shouldnt-learn-to-hit-until-later-teen-years|title=Medical doctor, NHL coach say kids shouldn\u2019t learn to hit until later teen years|date=August 24, 2010|website=TheHockeyNews|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"citizen\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/ottawa-citizen/20101107/282445640437138|title=HEADS-UP FOR HOCKEY: No agreement on how to fix concussions in youth sport|last=Scanlan|first=Wayne|date=November 7, 2010|via=PressReader|newspaper=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> Aubry called for instructing players that a body check is a way of separating an opponent from the puck, rather than continuing the perception of hockey as a rough sport where putting an opposing player through the boards is considered part of the game,<ref name=\"citizen\" /> given that no safety equipment could prevent serious injuries such as the [[Ronny Keller]] incident resulting in paraplegia.<ref name=\"B\u00e9land\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/sports/hockey/201303/07/01-4628664-un-joueur-suisse-paralyse-la-pire-blessure-au-hockey.php|title=Un joueur suisse paralys\u00e9: La pire blessure au hockey|language=French||last=B\u00e9land|first=Gabriel|date=March 7, 2013|website=La Presse|access-date=August 1, 2018}}</ref> Aubry has also testified before the [[Canadian International Trade Tribunal]] as an expert witness on the safety of hockey equipment.<ref name=\"CITT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.citt.gc.ca/en/file/1116/download%3Ftoken%3DvoNulTlm|title=Appeal No. AP-96-007|date=August 29, 1997|website=Canadian International Trade Tribunal|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAubry stated that awareness on the long-term effects of concussions increased partially because of the injuries to [[Sidney Crosby]], but noted that physicians in the [[National Hockey League]] still disagree on when players are healthy enough to return to play.<ref name=\"CMAJ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmaj.ca/content/cmaj/early/2011/12/19/cmaj.109-4080.full.pdf|title=Physicians must be brought up to speed on concussion risks|last=Fallis|first=Jordan|date=December 19, 2011|website=Canadian Medical Association Journal|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He was one of the authors in the 2017 report ''Can visible signs predict concussion diagnosis in the National Hockey League?''<ref name=\"BJSM\">{{cite web|url=https://bjsm.bmj.com/content/early/2017/04/04/bjsports-2016-097090.info|title=Can visible signs predict concussion diagnosis in the National Hockey League?|date=April 4, 2017|publisher=British Journal of Sports Medicine|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> He assessed Senators' player [[Clarke MacArthur]] for [[post-concussion syndrome]],<ref name=\"Clinton\">{{cite web|url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/senators-macarthur-will-need-to-pass-neuro-psych-test-in-order-to-play-again|title=Senators\u2019 MacArthur will need to pass \u2018neuro-psych test\u2019 in order to play again|last=Clinton|first=Jared|date=December 13, 2016|website=TheHockeyNews|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> and said that given MacArthur's history, it would be too risky to return to play.<ref name=\"Garrioch\">{{cite web|url=https://ottawasun.com/2017/01/20/ottawa-senators-decide-to-shut-down-clarke-macarthur-for-remainder-of-season/wcm/d1bc30e6-5496-4d2c-96a8-8245457c19c6|title=Ottawa Senators decide to shut down Clarke MacArthur for remainder of season|last=Garrioch|first=Bruce|date=January 20, 2017|website=Ottawa Sun|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> He also cited research that in-game concussion protocols need to be strictly adhered to, and reiterated the need to evaluate players at the first sign of possible concussion, rather than staying in the game.<ref name=\"Klein\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thespec.com/sports-story/4154849-researchers-call-for-safer-hockey-after-injuries-sideline-3-nhl-players-in-season-s-first-eight-days/|title=Researchers call for safer hockey after injuries sideline 3 NHL players in season\u2019s first eight days|last=Klein|first=Jeff Z.|date=October 12, 2013|website=Hamilton Spectator|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He recommends a proactive approach to ensure players do not return to play too soon, citing recent studies on the numbers of concussions in minor ice hockey, and specifically at the peewee age level when players are typically exposed to body checking for the first time.<ref name=\"sportsnet\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/hockey-summit/|title=Hockey Summit: Talk moves to injuries|date=August 24, 2010|website=Sportsnet.ca|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He also spoke at the [[Canadian Academy of Sport and Exercise Medicine]] (CASEM) conference in August 2018, to address post-concussion syndrome, and methods for diagnosis.<ref name=\"CASEM\">{{cite web|url=https://casem-acmse.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/2018-Hockey-Preliminary-Program-FINAL5-4.pdf|title=Keep Your Edge|date=August 17, 2018|pages=2,4,6|website=Canadian Academy of Sport and Exercise Medicine|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===International hockey===\nAubry has served as the CMO of the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]] (IIHF) since 1998.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"Pashby\">{{cite web|url=http://www.drpashby.ca/2006/11/dr-mark-aubry-2006-dr-tom-pashby-sports-safety-award|title=Dr. Mark Aubry \u2013 2006 Dr. Tom Pashby Sports Safety Award|date=November 18, 2006|website=Dr. Pashby Sports Safety Fund|access-date=August 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814002052/http://www.drpashby.ca/2006/11/dr-mark-aubry-2006-dr-tom-pashby-sports-safety-award|archive-date=August 14, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> He took over the CMO position from [[Wolf-Dieter Montag]], who had served in the role since 1975.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gots.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/CV_Montag.pdf|title=Wolf-Dieter Montag \u2013 Curriculum Vitae|date=19 November 2014|website=Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Orthop\u00e4disch-Traumatologische Sportmedizin|language=de|page=2}}</ref> Aubry also sits on the medical commission of the [[International Olympic Committee]].<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> In this role, he advised against international travel to [[Beijing]] for the [[2003 Women's Ice Hockey World Championships]], which was ultimately cancelled because of the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS outbreak]].<ref name=\"SARS\">{{cite news|title=Women's hockey tourney canceled because of illness|newspaper=Colorado Springs Gazette|location=Colorado Springs, Colorado|date=March 31, 2003|page=64|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-31-2003-776152/}}{{free access}}</ref> In [[ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics]], Aubry stated that the drug which [[Mattias \u00d6hlund|Mattias Ohlund]] tested positive for was contained in the medicine given to him after eye surgery, and should not be considered a doping infraction.<ref name=\"Lebrun\">{{cite news|title=Ohlund will play in Olympic games|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|last=Lebrun|first=Pierre|author-link=Pierre LeBrun|date=January 22, 2002|page=10|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-22-2002-776127/}}{{free access}}</ref> In [[ice hockey at the 2014 Winter Olympics]], Aubry stated that [[Nicklas B\u00e4ckstr\u00f6m|Nicklas Backstrom]]'s positive test for [[pseudoephedrine]] was a result of [[Cetirizine|Zyrtec-D]] taken to treat [[sinusitis]], and it should not be considered a doping infraction.<ref name=\"Carrera\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/olympics/nicklas-backstrom-fails-ioc-doping-test-misses-gold-medal-olympic-hockey-game/2014/02/23/fec67726-9cc0-11e3-8112-52fdf646027b_story.html|title=Nicklas Backstrom fails IOC doping test, misses gold medal Olympic hockey game|last1=Carrera|first1=Katie|last2=Sheinin|first2=Dave|date=February 23, 2014|website=Washington Post|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"TheLocal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.se/20140223/dreams-of-hockey-gold-sabotaged-by-ioc-sweden|title=Hockey star's doping ban 'was political'|date=February 23, 2014|website=The Local|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> Since Aubry became CMO, IIHF competitions and the Winter Olympic Games, ice hockey officials have been instructed to penalize all hits to the head, and are critiqued for any such missed calls.<ref name=\"citizen\" /> Aubry was one of the authors of the 2017 report ''Concussions in international ice hockey championships and olympic winter games between 2006 and 2015''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/320847926_Concussions_in_international_ice_hockey_championships_and_olympic_winter_games_between_2006_and_2015|title=Concussions in international ice hockey championships and olympic winter games between 2006 and 2015|date=June 2017|website=Researchgate|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> He later spoke at a CASEM conference, discussing how the faults in how the IIHF reports injuries, and the lessons to be learned.<ref name=\"CASEM\" />\n\n===Hockey Canada===\n{{quote box|title=Hockey Canada concussion seminar|quote=\"The fight in reducing concussions is global in nature and needs the help of every participant in the sport to prevent this injury through fair play, enforcement of the rules and other measures.\"|source=&mdash;''Mark Aubry'', 2010<ref name=\"Perry\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/hockey-canada-set-to-host-concussion-seminar-1.925991|title=Hockey Canada set to host concussion seminar|last=Perry|first=Rod|date=2010-11-09|website=CBC Sports|access-date=2018-08-04}}</ref>|width=27.5%|align=right}}\n\nAubry has served as the CMO of [[Hockey Canada]] since 2004,<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"Pashby\" /> assisted in developing the Hockey Canada Safety Program, and is a part the safety program committee.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" />  He pushed for Hockey Canada to adopt [[zero tolerance]] rules for hits to the head, whether accidental or not, and recommended that teams have seminars on the risks of concussions.<ref name=\"CMAJ\" /> Since he became CMO, Hockey Canada now requires team trainers to complete a course on handling concussions,<ref name=\"citizen\" /> recommends that players with concussions get a [[medical certificate]] with a doctor's permission to play,<ref name=\"CMAJ\" /> and standardized the graduated implementation of checking skills through its age levels across Canada.<ref name=\"bodycheck\" /> Aubry has also pushed for educating on ice officials for calling hitting from behind infractions, in addition to checks to the head.<ref name=\"B\u00e9land\" /> Aubry published [[Influenza A virus subtype H1N1|H1N1 influenza]] preventative guidelines prior to the 2009\u201310 hockey season,<ref name=\"H1N1\">{{cite news|title=H1N1 had an impact on teams' operations this season|newspaper=Portage La Prairie Central Plains Herald Leader|location=Portage La Prairie, Manitoba|date=February 27, 2010|page=44|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-feb-27-2010-776138/}}{{free access}}</ref> and later issued guidelines for the use of water bottles and sports drinks, to prevent the spread of contagious viruses.<ref name=\"Mittelstaedt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/hockey-canada-shuns-sharing-of-bottles/article4291274/|title=Hockey Canada shuns sharing of bottles|last=Mittelstaedt|first=Martin|date=May 1, 2018|website=The Globe and Mail|access-date=August 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nAubry was given the Dr. [[Tom Pashby]] Sports Safety Fund Award in 2006, for his research on concussions and spinal cord injuries.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> He received the Mayor's Cup in 2011, for outstanding contributions to sport in [[Ottawa]].<ref name=\"MayorsCup\" /> He was named the recipient of the [[Paul Loicq Award]] in 2014, for contributions to international ice hockey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/dr-mark-aubry-will-receive-the-paul-loicq-award-for-contributions-to-hockey-through-research-on-spinal-injuries-and-concussions|title=Dr. Mark Aubry will receive the Paul Loicq Award for contributions to hockey through research on spinal injuries and concussions|date=April 22, 2014|website=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Paul Loicq Award}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aubry, Mark}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian physicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian physicians]]\n[[Category:Canada at the Winter Universiade]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey centres]]\n[[Category:Canadian sports physicians]]\n[[Category:Concussion activists]]\n[[Category:Hockey Canada personnel]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Quebec]]\n[[Category:International Ice Hockey Federation executives]]\n[[Category:Lecturers]]\n[[Category:Olympic team doctors]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Gee-Gees]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Lynx]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Renegades personnel]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Rough Riders personnel]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Senators executives]]\n[[Category:Paul Loicq Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Quebec]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rouyn-Noranda]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Mark Aubry\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1954|11|24}}\n| birth_place  = [[Noranda, Quebec]], Canada\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  = \n| alma_mater   = [[University of Ottawa]]\n| occupation   = [[Physician]]\n| years_active = 1981\u2013present \n| employer     = [[Ottawa Senators]] \n| known_for    = [[Sports medicine]] specialist, and [[Chief Medical Officer]] of the [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] and [[Hockey Canada]]\n| awards       = [[Paul Loicq Award]], Dr. [[Tom Pashby]] sports safety award \n}}\n\n'''Mark John Aubry''' (born November 24, 1954) is a Canadian [[physician]] and [[sports medicine]] specialist. He is the team physician for the [[Ottawa Senators]], and serves as the [[Chief Medical Officer]] of both the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]], and [[Hockey Canada]]. He researches and lectures on [[concussion]]s, plays a leadership role for safety in sport, and is an injury prevention activist in minor ice hockey. He is a recipient of the [[Paul Loicq Award]] for his international work, and the Dr. [[Tom Pashby]] sports safety award for Canada.\n\n==Early life==\nAubry was born November 24, 1954, in [[Noranda, Quebec]],<ref name=\"IIHF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iihf.com/home-of-hockey/news/iihf-hof-2014/|title=Paul Loicq Award: Dr Mark Aubry (CAN)|date=2014|website=IIHF|access-date=July 31, 2018}}</ref> and learned to speak both English and French.<ref name=\"cpso\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cpso.on.ca/DoctorDetails/Aubry-Mark-John/0028044-32867|title=Aubry, Mark John (CPSO#: 32867)|website=[[College of Physicians and Surgeons of Ontario]]|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> He attended [[Merivale High School]], and played hockey, football and baseball at school.<ref name=\"MayorsCup\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insideottawavalley.com/community-story/3803201-fury-s-zito-picked-for-top-male-coach-award/|title=Fury's Zito picked for top male coach award|date=January 21, 2011|website=InsideOttawaValley.com|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> Aubry began playing [[junior ice hockey]] as a [[Centre (ice hockey)|centreman]]; he is listed at 6 feet tall, and 180 pounds, for the [[Rockland Nationals|Ottawa M and W Rangers]] in the [[Central Canada Hockey League]] during the 1971\u201372 season.<ref name=\"hockeydb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=72733|title=Mark Aubry hockey statistics and profile|website=hockeydb|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> During the 1972\u201373 season, he was coached by future [[IIHF Hall of Fame]] inductee, [[Derek Holmes (ice hockey)|Derek Holmes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/leagues/seasons/teams/0032181973.html|title=Ottawa M and W Rangers 1972&ndash;73 roster and scoring statistics|website=hockeydb.com|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> Aubry won the most valuable player award and the sportsmanship award in the 1972\u201373 season with the Rangers, and won the sportsmanship award again in the 1973\u201374 season.<ref name=\"CCHL\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thecchl.ca/season-award-archives|title=Season Award Archives|website=Central Canada Hockey League|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> He then played for the [[Ottawa Gee-Gees]] during the 1974&ndash;75 and 1975&ndash;76 seasons,<ref name=\"hockeydb\" /><ref name=\"uottawa\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uottawa.ca/archives/sites/www.uottawa.ca.archives/files/hockey.pdf|title=Historique du hockey \u00e0 l'Universit\u00e9 d'Ottawa|language=french|website=University of Ottawa archives|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> while earning his medical degree.<ref name=\"dr-aubry\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeycanada.ca/en-ca/exclusive/quebec-hockey-summit/home/attendees/speakers/mark-aubry|title=Doctor Mark Aubry|website=Hockey Canada|access-date=July 31, 2018}}</ref> After playing, he worked as a trainer for the Gee-Gees.<ref name=\"MayorsCup\" />\n\n==Medical career==\nAubry graduated from the [[University of Ottawa]] in 1978.<ref name=\"cpso\" /> He established a [[family medicine]] office in [[Hull, Quebec]] on September, 18, 1981.<ref name=\"cpso\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> As of 2018, he is a director at the Ottawa Sport Medicine Centre,<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> and is a team physician for the [[Ottawa Senators]].<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/senators/team/front-office#medical-staff|title=Hockey Operations|website=Ottawa Senators|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> Aubry previously served as the team physician for the [[Ottawa 67's]] from 1996 to 2005,<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> the [[Ottawa Rough Riders]],<ref name=\"MayorsCup\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> the [[Ottawa Renegades]],<ref name=\"Renegades\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/opening-day-of-renegades-training-camp-highlighted-by-medicals-meetings-and-preparation/n-3168889|title=Opening day of Renegades training camp highlighted by medicals, meetings and preparation|date=May 28, 2005|website=OurSports Central|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> and the [[Ottawa Lynx]].<ref name=\"Pashby\" /> He was a trainer on [[minor ice hockey]] teams from 1989 to 2000, [[Chief Medical Officer]] (CMO) for the Canadian team at the [[1991 Winter Universiade]], and CMO of [[Canada at the 1992 Winter Olympics]] in [[Albertville]].<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" />\n\n===Sports medicine===\nAubry has spent significant time working in [[sports medicine]], lecturing on injury prevention, and researching [[concussion]]s and [[spinal cord]] injuries with respect to [[Checking (ice hockey)|body checking]] in ice hockey.<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /><ref name=\"Pashby\" /><ref name=\"bodycheck\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeyeasternontario.ca/docs/HC_Body_Checking_Brief_1.pdf|title=Hockey Canada\u2014Body Checking Brief|date=April 17, 2013|website=Hockey Eastern Ontario|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He helped organize three symposiums on sports concussions (2001 in [[Vienna]], 2004 in [[Prague]], and 2008 in [[Z\u00fcrich]]), to assist doctors in identifying and treating concussions.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> Aubry was one of the physicians consulted for the 2011 report ''Brain Injury Guide for Youth'',<ref name=\"Kutcher\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ontarioshores.ca/UserFiles/Servers/Server_6/File/PDFs/bi_teen_guide_4.pdf|title=Brain Injury Guide for Youth|last=Kutcher|first=Stan|date=2011|page=3|website=Ontario Shores|publisher=Teenmentalhealth.org|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> and was one of the medical experts that helped write the module ''Making Head Way in Sport'' released in 2014, for the Coaching Association of Canada to educate on when it is okay to return to play.<ref name=\"CAC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.coach.ca/making-head-way-in-sport-elearning-module-is-now-available-at-no-charge-p156794|title=Making Head Way in Sport eLearning module is now available at no charge|date=July 17, 2014|website=Coaching Association of Canada|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> Aubry has also spoken against focusing too much on one sport at a young age, as it has not only \"taken the fun out of it\", but also has physical and cultural risks in not developing the person.<ref name=\"Scanlan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/ottawa-citizen/20170322/281479276237544|title=Can sports be fun again?|last=Scanlan|first=Wayne|date=March 22, 2017|website=PressReader.com|publisher=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|title=World Hockey Summit|quote=\"We\u2019re exposing these kids to an increased risk of injury at an age where I think we should still be talking about skill development and having fun.\"|source=&mdash;''Mark Aubry'', 2010<ref name=\"Fitz-Gerald\" /><ref name=\"TheHockeyNews\" /><ref name=\"sportsnet\" />|width=27.5%|align=right}}\n\nAt the 2010 [[World Hockey Summit]], a joint project hosted by the National Hockey League, the [[National Hockey League Players' Association]], Hockey Canada, [[USA Hockey]], the IIHF, and the [[Canadian Hockey League]],<ref name=\"NHLPA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nhlpa.com/news/1-13651/whos-who-of-hockey-to-gather-for-world-hockey-summit|title=Who's Who of Hockey To Gather for World Hockey Summit|date=July 29, 2010|website=National Hockey League Players Association|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> Aubry called for raising the minimum age for body checking to 13 or 14 and eliminating hits from behind altogether.<ref name=\"Fitz-Gerald\" /><ref name=\"TheHockeyNews\" /> Based on his research and experience, he argued that children should be developing skills instead, as they are the most vulnerable to injury due to height and weight differences; he cited research which highlights risks of long-term effects for athletes who have had multiple concussions, specifically younger hockey players.<ref name=\"Fitz-Gerald\">{{cite news|title=Delay body checks till 13, 14, doc says|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|last1=Fitz-Gerald|first1=Sean|last2=Strong|first2=Gregory|date=August 25, 2010|page=24|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-25-2010-776136/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref name=\"TheHockeyNews\">{{cite web|url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/medical-doctor-nhl-coach-say-kids-shouldnt-learn-to-hit-until-later-teen-years|title=Medical doctor, NHL coach say kids shouldn\u2019t learn to hit until later teen years|date=August 24, 2010|website=TheHockeyNews|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"citizen\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/ottawa-citizen/20101107/282445640437138|title=HEADS-UP FOR HOCKEY: No agreement on how to fix concussions in youth sport|last=Scanlan|first=Wayne|date=November 7, 2010|via=PressReader|newspaper=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> Aubry called for instructing players that a body check is a way of separating an opponent from the puck, rather than continuing the perception of hockey as a rough sport where putting an opposing player through the boards is considered part of the game,<ref name=\"citizen\" /> given that no safety equipment could prevent serious injuries such as the [[Ronny Keller]] incident resulting in paraplegia.<ref name=\"B\u00e9land\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/sports/hockey/201303/07/01-4628664-un-joueur-suisse-paralyse-la-pire-blessure-au-hockey.php|title=Un joueur suisse paralys\u00e9: La pire blessure au hockey|language=French||last=B\u00e9land|first=Gabriel|date=March 7, 2013|website=La Presse|access-date=August 1, 2018}}</ref> Aubry has also testified before the [[Canadian International Trade Tribunal]] as an expert witness on the safety of hockey equipment.<ref name=\"CITT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.citt.gc.ca/en/file/1116/download%3Ftoken%3DvoNulTlm|title=Appeal No. AP-96-007|date=August 29, 1997|website=Canadian International Trade Tribunal|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAubry stated that awareness on the long-term effects of concussions increased partially because of the injuries to [[Sidney Crosby]], but noted that physicians in the [[National Hockey League]] still disagree on when players are healthy enough to return to play.<ref name=\"CMAJ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmaj.ca/content/cmaj/early/2011/12/19/cmaj.109-4080.full.pdf|title=Physicians must be brought up to speed on concussion risks|last=Fallis|first=Jordan|date=December 19, 2011|website=Canadian Medical Association Journal|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He was one of the authors in the 2017 report ''Can visible signs predict concussion diagnosis in the National Hockey League?''<ref name=\"BJSM\">{{cite web|url=https://bjsm.bmj.com/content/early/2017/04/04/bjsports-2016-097090.info|title=Can visible signs predict concussion diagnosis in the National Hockey League?|date=April 4, 2017|publisher=British Journal of Sports Medicine|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> He assessed Senators' player [[Clarke MacArthur]] for [[post-concussion syndrome]],<ref name=\"Clinton\">{{cite web|url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/senators-macarthur-will-need-to-pass-neuro-psych-test-in-order-to-play-again|title=Senators\u2019 MacArthur will need to pass \u2018neuro-psych test\u2019 in order to play again|last=Clinton|first=Jared|date=December 13, 2016|website=TheHockeyNews|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> and said that given MacArthur's history, it would be too risky to return to play.<ref name=\"Garrioch\">{{cite web|url=https://ottawasun.com/2017/01/20/ottawa-senators-decide-to-shut-down-clarke-macarthur-for-remainder-of-season/wcm/d1bc30e6-5496-4d2c-96a8-8245457c19c6|title=Ottawa Senators decide to shut down Clarke MacArthur for remainder of season|last=Garrioch|first=Bruce|date=January 20, 2017|website=Ottawa Sun|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> He also cited research that in-game concussion protocols need to be strictly adhered to, and reiterated the need to evaluate players at the first sign of possible concussion, rather than staying in the game.<ref name=\"Klein\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thespec.com/sports-story/4154849-researchers-call-for-safer-hockey-after-injuries-sideline-3-nhl-players-in-season-s-first-eight-days/|title=Researchers call for safer hockey after injuries sideline 3 NHL players in season\u2019s first eight days|last=Klein|first=Jeff Z.|date=October 12, 2013|website=Hamilton Spectator|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He recommends a proactive approach to ensure players do not return to play too soon, citing recent studies on the numbers of concussions in minor ice hockey, and specifically at the peewee age level when players are typically exposed to body checking for the first time.<ref name=\"sportsnet\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/hockey-summit/|title=Hockey Summit: Talk moves to injuries|date=August 24, 2010|website=Sportsnet.ca|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He also spoke at the [[Canadian Academy of Sport and Exercise Medicine]] (CASEM) conference in August 2018, to address post-concussion syndrome, and methods for diagnosis.<ref name=\"CASEM\">{{cite web|url=https://casem-acmse.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/2018-Hockey-Preliminary-Program-FINAL5-4.pdf|title=Keep Your Edge|date=August 17, 2018|pages=2,4,6|website=Canadian Academy of Sport and Exercise Medicine|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===International hockey===\nAubry has served as the CMO of the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]] (IIHF) since 1998.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"Pashby\">{{cite web|url=http://www.drpashby.ca/2006/11/dr-mark-aubry-2006-dr-tom-pashby-sports-safety-award|title=Dr. Mark Aubry \u2013 2006 Dr. Tom Pashby Sports Safety Award|date=November 18, 2006|website=Dr. Pashby Sports Safety Fund|access-date=August 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814002052/http://www.drpashby.ca/2006/11/dr-mark-aubry-2006-dr-tom-pashby-sports-safety-award|archive-date=August 14, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> He took over the CMO position from [[Wolf-Dieter Montag]], who had served in the role since 1975.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gots.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/CV_Montag.pdf|title=Wolf-Dieter Montag \u2013 Curriculum Vitae|date=19 November 2014|website=Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Orthop\u00e4disch-Traumatologische Sportmedizin|language=de|page=2}}</ref> Aubry also sits on the medical commission of the [[International Olympic Committee]].<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> In this role, he advised against international travel to [[Beijing]] for the [[2003 Women's Ice Hockey World Championships]], which was ultimately cancelled because of the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS outbreak]].<ref name=\"SARS\">{{cite news|title=Women's hockey tourney canceled because of illness|newspaper=Colorado Springs Gazette|location=Colorado Springs, Colorado|date=March 31, 2003|page=64|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-31-2003-776152/}}{{free access}}</ref> In [[ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics]], Aubry stated that the drug which [[Mattias \u00d6hlund|Mattias Ohlund]] tested positive for was contained in the medicine given to him after eye surgery, and should not be considered a doping infraction.<ref name=\"Lebrun\">{{cite news|title=Ohlund will play in Olympic games|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|last=Lebrun|first=Pierre|author-link=Pierre LeBrun|date=January 22, 2002|page=10|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-22-2002-776127/}}{{free access}}</ref> In [[ice hockey at the 2014 Winter Olympics]], Aubry stated that [[Nicklas B\u00e4ckstr\u00f6m|Nicklas Backstrom]]'s positive test for [[pseudoephedrine]] was a result of [[Cetirizine|Zyrtec-D]] taken to treat [[sinusitis]], and it should not be considered a doping infraction.<ref name=\"Carrera\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/olympics/nicklas-backstrom-fails-ioc-doping-test-misses-gold-medal-olympic-hockey-game/2014/02/23/fec67726-9cc0-11e3-8112-52fdf646027b_story.html|title=Nicklas Backstrom fails IOC doping test, misses gold medal Olympic hockey game|last1=Carrera|first1=Katie|last2=Sheinin|first2=Dave|date=February 23, 2014|website=Washington Post|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"TheLocal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.se/20140223/dreams-of-hockey-gold-sabotaged-by-ioc-sweden|title=Hockey star's doping ban 'was political'|date=February 23, 2014|website=The Local|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> Since Aubry became CMO, IIHF competitions and the Winter Olympic Games, ice hockey officials have been instructed to penalize all hits to the head, and are critiqued for any such missed calls.<ref name=\"citizen\" /> Aubry was one of the authors of the 2017 report ''Concussions in international ice hockey championships and olympic winter games between 2006 and 2015''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/320847926_Concussions_in_international_ice_hockey_championships_and_olympic_winter_games_between_2006_and_2015|title=Concussions in international ice hockey championships and olympic winter games between 2006 and 2015|date=June 2017|website=Researchgate|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> He later spoke at a CASEM conference, discussing how the faults in how the IIHF reports injuries, and the lessons to be learned.<ref name=\"CASEM\" />\n\n===Hockey Canada===\n{{quote box|title=Hockey Canada concussion seminar|quote=\"The fight in reducing concussions is global in nature and needs the help of every participant in the sport to prevent this injury through fair play, enforcement of the rules and other measures.\"|source=&mdash;''Mark Aubry'', 2010<ref name=\"Perry\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/hockey-canada-set-to-host-concussion-seminar-1.925991|title=Hockey Canada set to host concussion seminar|last=Perry|first=Rod|date=2010-11-09|website=CBC Sports|access-date=2018-08-04}}</ref>|width=27.5%|align=right}}\n\nAubry has served as the CMO of [[Hockey Canada]] since 2004,<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"Pashby\" /> assisted in developing the Hockey Canada Safety Program, and is a part the safety program committee.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" />  He pushed for Hockey Canada to adopt [[zero tolerance]] rules for hits to the head, whether accidental or not, and recommended that teams have seminars on the risks of concussions.<ref name=\"CMAJ\" /> Since he became CMO, Hockey Canada now requires team trainers to complete a course on handling concussions,<ref name=\"citizen\" /> recommends that players with concussions get a [[medical certificate]] with a doctor's permission to play,<ref name=\"CMAJ\" /> and standardized the graduated implementation of checking skills through its age levels across Canada.<ref name=\"bodycheck\" /> Aubry has also pushed for educating on ice officials for calling hitting from behind infractions, in addition to checks to the head.<ref name=\"B\u00e9land\" /> Aubry published [[Influenza A virus subtype H1N1|H1N1 influenza]] preventative guidelines prior to the 2009\u201310 hockey season,<ref name=\"H1N1\">{{cite news|title=H1N1 had an impact on teams' operations this season|newspaper=Portage La Prairie Central Plains Herald Leader|location=Portage La Prairie, Manitoba|date=February 27, 2010|page=44|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-feb-27-2010-776138/}}{{free access}}</ref> and later issued guidelines for the use of water bottles and sports drinks, to prevent the spread of contagious viruses.<ref name=\"Mittelstaedt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/hockey-canada-shuns-sharing-of-bottles/article4291274/|title=Hockey Canada shuns sharing of bottles|last=Mittelstaedt|first=Martin|date=May 1, 2018|website=The Globe and Mail|access-date=August 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nAubry was given the Dr. [[Tom Pashby]] Sports Safety Fund Award in 2006, for his research on concussions and spinal cord injuries.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> He received the Mayor's Cup in 2011, for outstanding contributions to sport in [[Ottawa]].<ref name=\"MayorsCup\" /> He was named the recipient of the [[Paul Loicq Award]] in 2014, for contributions to international ice hockey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/dr-mark-aubry-will-receive-the-paul-loicq-award-for-contributions-to-hockey-through-research-on-spinal-injuries-and-concussions|title=Dr. Mark Aubry will receive the Paul Loicq Award for contributions to hockey through research on spinal injuries and concussions|date=April 22, 2014|website=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Paul Loicq Award}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aubry, Mark}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian physicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian physicians]]\n[[Category:Canada at the Winter Universiade]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey centres]]\n[[Category:Canadian sports physicians]]\n[[Category:Concussion activists]]\n[[Category:Hockey Canada personnel]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Quebec]]\n[[Category:International Ice Hockey Federation executives]]\n[[Category:Lecturers]]\n[[Category:Olympic team doctors]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Gee-Gees]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Lynx]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Renegades personnel]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Rough Riders personnel]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Senators executives]]\n[[Category:Paul Loicq Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Quebec]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rouyn-Noranda]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Flibirigit", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSports medicine:tweak punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Aubry"}
{"title_page": "Leo Nocentelli", "text_new": "{{short description|American musician and songwriter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Leo Nocentelli\n| image = Leo-Nocentelli-new-york-city-august-3-2006.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption = Nocentelli performing in 2006\n| background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1946|6|15}}<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" />\n| birth_place = [[New Orleans, Louisiana]]\n| instrument = Guitar\n| label = \n| genre = [[Funk]], [[R&B]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[Rock music|rock]], [[jazz]]\n| occupation = Musician, songwriter\n| years_active = Late 1950s\u2013present\n| associated_acts = {{nowrap|[[The Meters]]}}, {{nowrap|Neville Sounds}}, {{nowrap|The Funky Meters}}, {{nowrap|The Meter Men}}\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Leo Nocentelli''' (born June 15, 1946) is an American musician and songwriter best known as a founding member and lead guitarist of the [[funk]] band [[The Meters]]. He wrote the original versions of several funk classics such as \"[[Cissy Strut]]\" and \"Hey Pocky A-Way\". As a session musician he has recorded with a variety of notable artists such as [[Dr. John]], [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]] and [[Etta James]]. He is the recipient of a Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award as a member of The Meters.\n\n==Career==\n\nNocentelli grew up in the [[Irish Channel, New Orleans|Irish Channel]] and [[Seventh Ward, New Orleans|Seventh Ward]] neighborhoods of New Orleans. He was encouraged by his father to pursue music. He played [[ukulele]] at an early age and started on guitar at age twelve.<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /><ref name=\"ln-louisiana music\" /> He gravitated to jazz and was influenced by jazz guitarists [[Charlie Christian]], [[Barney Kessel]], [[Johnny Smith]] and [[Kenny Burrell]].<ref name=\"ln-allmusic-bio\" /> His first professional gig was at age thirteen.<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /> By age fourteen he was backing notable musicians such as [[Otis Redding]] and [[Clyde McPhatter]].<ref name=\"ln-louisiana music\" /> He played jazz, [[Dixieland]], [[rhythm and blues]], and [[Rock and roll|rock]].<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2011\" />{{rp|page=2}} He joined the [[The Hawketts|Hawketts]] and developed a reputation as a guitarist. At age seventeen he did session work for Motown acts including the [[The Supremes|Supremes]], [[The Temptations|Temptations]], and [[The Spinners (American R&B group)|Spinners]].<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /><ref name=\"ln-musical gumbo\" />\n\nIn 1964 he was drafted and served in the army for two years. During [[Leave (U.S. military)|leaves]] he did session work in New Orleans. After the service he joined Art Neville and the Neville Sounds, at the time a recently founded seven-piece band. By 1968 the band consisted of four members: Nocentelli, [[Art Neville]], [[George Porter Jr.|George Porter]], and [[Ziggy Modeliste]].<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /> The band had a fluid style and each instrument was free to go anywhere musically.<ref name=\"ln-louisiana music\" /> The band performed dance-style rhythm and blues at the Ivanhoe nightclub six nights a week. On Sundays, Nocentelli, Porter, and Modeliste performed jazz gigs.<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /><ref name=\"ln-musical gumbo\" /> Nocentelli said his bandmates were his biggest influence and called his experience up to this point in time the learning phase of his career.<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2004\" /><ref name=\"ln-blues blog\" />\n\nThe band released two singles as [[The Meters]], \"Sophisticated Cissy\" and \"[[Cissy Strut]]\", both originally written by Nocentelli.<ref name=\"ln-hotg-singles-2011\" /><ref name=\"ln-vintage2002\" /> The commercial success of \"Cissy Strut\" became an impetus for the band's subsequent recording career as The Meters.<ref name=\"ln-vintage2002\" /> From 1969 to 1977 the band released eight studio albums, with Nocentelli as one of the primary songwriters.<ref name=\"ln-zig2008\" /> He wrote the original versions of funk songs such as \"People Say\" and \"Hey Pocky A-Way\".<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2004\" /><ref name=\"ln-gibson-2010\" /> Early on, improvisation was a major part of song development.<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2012\" />{{rp|page=2}} Though the band gained notoriety in the music community, the lack of commercial success along with managerial and artistic factors gave way to their disbandment in late 1970s.<ref name=\"ln-am-meters-bio\" /><ref name=\"ln-musical gumbo\" />\n\nThroughout the 1960s and 1970s, Nocentelli wrote, co-wrote and did session work \u2013 mostly in [[Cosimo Matassa|Cosimo]], [[Allen Toussaint#Sansu: Soul and early New Orleans funk|Sansu]], and [[Sea-Saint Studios|Sea-Saint]] studios.<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /><ref name=\"ln-allmusic-bio\" /><ref name=\"ln-jambands-2004\" /><ref name=\"ln-sundazed-2002\" /> As songwriter and producer, he learned from and was influenced by [[Allen Toussaint]].<ref name=\"ln-westword-2009\" /><ref name=\"ln-nola-dec2015\" /> He backed a variety of artists such as [[Dr. John]], [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]], [[Albert King]], [[Etta James]], [[Joe Cocker]], [[Earl King]], [[Chris Kenner]], and [[Betty Harris]].<ref name=\"ln-sundazed-2002\" /><ref name=\"ln-allmusic-bio\" /><ref name=\"ln-jambands-2004\" />\n\nIn the early 1980s Nocentelli toured with [[Jimmy Buffett]]. He moved to Los Angeles in 1982.<ref name=\"ln-nola-dec2015\" /> He continued to do session work and performed regularly with former bandmate George Porter as GEO/LEO.<ref name=\"ln-vintage2002\" /><ref name=\"ln-gibson-2010\" /> He also remained close with Modeliste, who had moved to the [[San Francisco Bay Area]]. They performed in various quartet formations and released a live album titled ''[[Nocentelli: Live in San Francisco]]''.<ref name=\"ln-offbeat-may2015\" /><ref name=\"ln-blues-access\" /> At one of their shows in 1989, Nocentelli and Porter invited Modeliste and Neville on stage. The impromptu performance was the first reunion of the original Meters.<ref name=\"ln-vintage2002\" /> The same year Nocentelli, Neville, and Porter formed The Funky Meters with [[Russell Batiste Jr.|Russell Batiste]] on drums. Nocentelli performed with the reincarnated lineup until 1993.<ref name=\"ln-funk-third ear\" />\n\nHe briefly moved back to New Orleans in the early 1990s and returned to Los Angeles in 1992.<ref name=\"ln-offbeat-may2015\" /> He continued to perform with two Meters-inspired lineups: The Meter Men and The Meters Experience. The Meter Men are Nocentelli, Porter, and Modeliste with [[Page McConnell]] on keyboards; variations included keyboardists [[Galactic|Rich Vogel]], [[Papa Grows Funk|John Gros]], and drummer Russell Batiste.<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2012\" /><ref name=\"ln-nola2015perform\" /> The Meters Experience is Nocentelli in various quartets with [[Bernie Worrell]], [[Bill Dickens]], [[Oteil Burbridge]], [[Al Di Meola]], [[God Street Wine|Jason Crosby]], George Laks, Albert Margolis, Jamal Batiste, Ricky Cortez, Felix Pollard, and others.<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2011\" /><ref name=\"ln-gibson-2010\" /><ref name=\"ln-gratefulweb-2015\" />\n\nEarly on, Nocentelli used a [[Gibson ES-175]] hollow body guitar. He switched to a semi-hollow [[Fender Starcaster]] in mid-1970s. Around 2001 he switched to the semi-hollow [[Gibson ES-335]].<ref name=\"ln-vintage2002\" /><ref name=\"ln-sundazed-2002\" /> Nocentelli has performed in several reunions with the original Meters lineup.<ref name=\"ln-nola-aug2011\" /><ref name=\"ln-gratefulweb-2015\" /> He moved to New Orleans in 2015 and continues to perform.<ref name=\"ln-nola-dec2015\" /> He received a [[Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award]] in 2018 as a member of The Meters.<ref name=\"ln-lifetime-grammy\" />\n\n==Style==\nNocentelli was self-taught. In his early teens he emulated jazz guitarists while listening to [[phonograph records]].<ref name=\"ln-allmusic-bio\" /><ref name=\"ln-jambands-2004\" /> He was drawn to jazz, but to survive professionally he had to become proficient in multiple genres.<ref name=\"ln-allmusic-bio\" /><ref name=\"ln-jambands-2011\" /> In 1960s and 1970s he was part of an era in which New Orleans jazz gave way to rhythm and blues, and funk.<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /><ref>Berry 1992, ''Up from the Cradle of Jazz'', pp. 16, 192, 196.</ref> Nocentelli's band, The Meters, were innovative and set the stylistic tone of [[Funk#History|New Orleans funk]].<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /><ref name=\"ln-am-meters-bio\" /> The band's early works were rooted in improvisation.<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2012\" /><ref name=\"ln-offbeat-art-george\" /> According to Nocentelli, genres are relative and he alludes to incorporating different genres in his style.<ref name=\"ln-blues blog\" /><ref name=\"ln-jambands-2011\" /> He said in funk as well as in [[rhythm guitar]] you have to complement and react to what you hear, and said that is not a teachable skill.<ref name=\"ln-gibson-2010\" /> In addition to live performance and session work, songwriting was a significant part of Nocentelli's contribution.<ref name=\"ln-zig2008\" /><ref name=\"ln-vintage2002\" />\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|The Meters#Discography}}\n\n===As leader===\n* ''[[Nocentelli: Live in San Francisco]]'' ([[DJM Records|DJM]], 1997)\n* ''Rhythm & Rhymes Part 1'' (TLB, 2009)<ref name=\"ln-rhythm-EP\" />\n* ''The Secrets of Funk: Using it and Fusing it !'' (2003) \u2013 instructional DVD<ref name=\"ln-dvd-release\" />\n\n===With others===\nCredits partly adapted from [[AllMusic]].<ref name=\"ln-am-bio-credits\" />\n{{Expand list|date=March 2016}}\n\n* ''[[Nightbirds]]'' ([[Epic Records|Epic]], 1974) with [[Labelle]]\n* ''[[Sneakin' Sally Through the Alley]]'' ([[Island Records|Island]], 1974) with [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]]\n* ''[[The Wild Tchoupitoulas (album)|The Wild Tchoupitoulas]]'' ([[Mango Records|Mango]], 1976) with [[The Wild Tchoupitoulas]]\n* ''[[Patti LaBelle (album)|Patti LaBelle]]'' (Epic, 1977) with [[Patti LaBelle]]\n* ''[[Changes (Etta James album)|Changes]]'' ([[MCA Records|MCA]], 1980) with [[Etta James]]\n* ''[[On the Line (Michael Wycoff album)|On the Line]]'' ([[RCA Records|RCA]], 1983) with [[Michael Wycoff]] \n* ''Let My People Go'' ([[Qwest Records|Quest]], 1985) with [[The Winans]]\n* ''[[Winner in You]]'' (MCA, 1986) with Patti LaBelle\n* ''[[Tenderness (Kip Hanrahan album)|Tenderness]]'' (American Clave, 1990) with [[Kip Hanrahan]]\n* ''[[Storyville (album)|Storyville]]'' ([[Geffen Records|Geffen]], 1991) with [[Robbie Robertson]]\n* ''[[Us (Peter Gabriel album)|Us]]'' (Geffen, 1992) with [[Peter Gabriel]]\n* ''Southern Exposure'' ([[Jive Records|Jive]], 1993) with [[Maceo Parker]]\n* ''Urban Blues Re: Newell'' ([[Stony Plain Records|Sony Plain]], 1995) with [[King Biscuit Boy]]\n* ''Connected'' (NYNO, 1996) with [[Allen Toussaint]]\n* ''Rock and Roll Doctor: Lowell George Tribute'' ([[CMC International|CMC]], 1997) with various artists\n* ''[[Matriarch of the Blues]]'' (Private Music, 2000) with Etta James\n* ''[[Big Wide Grin]]'' (Sony, 2001) with [[Keb' Mo']]\n* ''Sing Me Back Home'' ([[Sony BMG]], 2006) with New Orleans Social Club<ref name=\"ln-am-review-singhome\" />\n* ''Unlock Your Mind'' ([[Rounder Records|Rounder]], 2012) with [[The Soul Rebels]]\n* ''Parking Lot Symphony'' ([[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]], 2017) with [[Trombone Shorty]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YMItAAAAYAAJ|title=Up from the Cradle of Jazz|author1=Jason Berry|author2= Jonathan Foose|author3=Tad Jones|publisher=Da Capo Press|year=1992|accessdate=November 17, 2015|isbn=9780306804939|pages=190\u2013200}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-allmusic-bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/leo-nocentelli-mn0000975844/biography|title=Allmusic: Leo Nocentelli \u2013 biography|publisher=Allmusic.com|accessdate=November 12, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505230138/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/leo-nocentelli-mn0000975844/biography|archivedate=May 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-vintage2002\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vintageguitar.com/2927/leo-nocentelli/|title=Leo Nocentelli \u2013 A Meter Keeps Running|author=John Heidt|publisher=Vintage Guitar magazine|date=September 2002|accessdate=November 12, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906094843/http://www.vintageguitar.com/2927/leo-nocentelli/|archivedate=September 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-louisiana music\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XIPRngEACAAJ|title=Louisiana Music: A Journey from R&B to Zydeco, Jazz to Country, Blues to Gospel...|author=Rick Koster|publisher=Da Capo Press|year=2002|accessdate=November 12, 2015|isbn=9780306804939|pages=97\u2013105}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-zig2008\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uqe8_iasA5Y#t=5m49s|title=New Orleans Drum Summit: David Kunian with Joseph \"Smokey\" Johnson, Zigaboo Modeliste, Bob French \u2013 video, recorded 2008|publisher=Youtube.com, Ponderosa Stomp Channel|date=December 15, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629032006/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uqe8_iasA5Y|archivedate=June 29, 2017|url-status=live|quote=Leo Nocentelli was one of the premier writers of the group and he always had this, this real, aggressive with songwriting and stuff like that.}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2004\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jambands.com/features/2004/05/29/used-with-leo-nocentelli|title=Used with Leo Nocentelli|author=Andy Tennille|publisher=jambands.com|date=May 29, 2004|accessdate=October 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814103351/http://www.jambands.com/features/2004/05/29/used-with-leo-nocentelli|archivedate=August 14, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-musical gumbo\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/musicalgumbomusi00lich|url-access=registration|title=Musical Gumbo: The Music of New Orleans|author1=Grace Lichtenstein|author2=Laura Dankner|publisher=W.W. Norton|year=1993|accessdate=October 8, 2017|isbn=9780393034684|pages=[https://archive.org/details/musicalgumbomusi00lich/page/153 153]\u2013160}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jambands.com/features/2011/01/25/leo-nocentelli-and-that-original-spark/|title=Leo Nocentelli and That Original Spark|author=Randy Ray|publisher=jambands.com|date=January 25, 2011|accessdate=October 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504203730/http://www.jambands.com/features/2011/01/25/leo-nocentelli-and-that-original-spark|archivedate=May 4, 2011|url-status=live}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20161222025734/http://www.jambands.com/features/2011/01/25/leo-nocentelli-and-that-original-spark?2 Archive page 2]</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-blues blog\">{{cite web|url=http://blues.gr/profiles/blogs/interview-leo-nocentelli-meters-new-orleans|title=Marvelous Leo Nocentelli of Meters talks about New Orleans culture, his experiences, and Muhammed Ali|author=Michalis Limnios|publisher=blues.gr|date=March 4, 2013|accessdate=October 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920083354/http://blues.gr/profiles/blogs/interview-leo-nocentelli-meters-new-orleans|archivedate=September 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2012\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jambands.com/features/2012/11/07/when-leo-met-leo-a-conversation-with-leo-nocentelli-page-mcconnell-and-george-porter-jr|title=When Leo Met Leo: A Conversation with Leo Nocentelli, Page McConnell and George Porter Jr.|publisher=jambands.com|date=November 7, 2012|accessdate=October 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126133210/http://www.jambands.com/features/2012/11/07/when-leo-met-leo-a-conversation-with-leo-nocentelli-page-mcconnell-and-george-porter-jr|archivedate=November 26, 2016|url-status=live}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20171008151544/http://www.jambands.com/features/2012/11/07/when-leo-met-leo-a-conversation-with-leo-nocentelli-page-mcconnell-and-george-porter-jr?2 Archive page 2], [https://web.archive.org/web/20171008151624/http://www.jambands.com/features/2012/11/07/when-leo-met-leo-a-conversation-with-leo-nocentelli-page-mcconnell-and-george-porter-jr?3 Archive page 3]</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-hotg-singles-2011\">{{cite web|url=http://homeofthegroove.blogspot.com/2011/06/sissy-variations-or-queen-of-funky.html|title=The Sissy variations or The Queen of Funky Dances|author=Dan Phillips|publisher=Home of the Groove|date=June 18, 2011|accessdate=October 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011013641/http://homeofthegroove.blogspot.com/2011/06/sissy-variations-or-queen-of-funky.html|archivedate=October 11, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-am-meters-bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-meters-mn0000402872/biography|title=Allmusic \u2013 The Meters \u2013 biography|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=October 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016230324/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-meters-mn0000402872/biography|archivedate=October 16, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-sundazed-2002\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sundazed.com/scene/exclusives/leo_nocentelli_exclus.html|title=Leo Nocentelli|author=Efram Turchick|publisher=sundazed.com|date=January 22, 2002|accessdate=October 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725103621/http://www.sundazed.com/scene/exclusives/leo_nocentelli_exclus.html|archivedate=July 25, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-westword-2009\">{{cite web|url=http://www.westword.com/music/qanda-with-leo-nocentelli-of-the-meters-5715188|title=Q&A with Leo Nocentelli of the Meters|author=Tom Murphy|publisher=Westword|date=December 23, 2009|accessdate=October 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121043533/http://www.westword.com/music/qanda-with-leo-nocentelli-of-the-meters-5715188|archivedate=January 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-nola-dec2015\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nola.com/music/index.ssf/2015/12/leo_nocentelli_meters_tipitina.html|title=The Meters' guitarist Leo Nocentelli returns home with the same passion for New Orleans' music|author=Chelsea Brasted|publisher=nola.com|date=December 8, 2015|accessdate=October 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105081504/http://www.nola.com/music/index.ssf/2015/12/leo_nocentelli_meters_tipitina.html|archivedate=November 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-am-review-singhome\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/sing-me-back-home-mw0000402086|title=Allmusic: Sing Me Back Home \u2013 review|author=Steve Haggett|publisher=AllMusic|date=2006|accessdate=October 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906062853/https://www.allmusic.com/album/sing-me-back-home-mw0000402086|archivedate=September 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-am-bio-credits\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/leo-nocentelli-mn0000975844/credits|title=Allmusic: Leo Nocentelli \u2013 credits|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=October 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505192518/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/leo-nocentelli-mn0000975844/credits|archivedate=May 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-offbeat-may2015\">{{cite web|url=http://www.offbeat.com/articles/leo-nocentellis-nocentelli/|title=Leo Nocentelli's Nocentelli|author=Keith Spera|publisher=OffBeat|date=May 1, 1995|accessdate=October 10, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305073638/http://www.offbeat.com/articles/leo-nocentellis-nocentelli/|archivedate=March 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-blues-access\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bluesaccess.com/No_34/reviews/nocentelli.html|title=Nocentelli \u2013 Live in San Francisco|author=John Koetzner|publisher=Blues Access magazine|date=Summer 1998|issue=34|accessdate=October 10, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106163616/http://www.bluesaccess.com/No_34/reviews/nocentelli.html|archivedate=January 6, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-funk-third ear\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RIEjkWXZdrMC&pg=PA164#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Funk, Third Ear: The Essential Listening Companion|author=Dave Thompson|publisher=Hal Leonard|year=2001|accessdate=October 10, 2017|isbn=9780879306298|pages=164\u2013169}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-gibson-2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gibson.com/news-lifestyle/features/en-us/leo-nocentelli-0716.aspx|title=The Gibson Interview \u2013 Leo Nocentelli of The Meters|author=Bryan Wawzenek|publisher=Gibson.com|date=July 16, 2010|accessdate=October 10, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515121831/http://www.gibson.com/news-lifestyle/features/en-us/leo-nocentelli-0716.aspx|archivedate=May 15, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-nola2015perform\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nola.com/jazzfest/index.ssf/2014/11/the_meter_men_featuring_phishs.html|title=The Meter Men, featuring Phish's Page McConnell, to headline Joy Theater during 2015 New Orleans Jazz Fest|author=Keith Spera|publisher=nola.com|date=November 10, 2014|accessdate=October 10, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150531194124/http://www.nola.com/jazzfest/index.ssf/2014/11/the_meter_men_featuring_phishs.html|archivedate=May 31, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-gratefulweb-2015\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gratefulweb.com/articles/grateful-web-interview-leo-nocentelli|title=Grateful Web Interview with Leo Nocentelli|author=Dylan Muhlberg|publisher=gratefulweb.com|date=May 11, 2015|accessdate=October 10, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925012110/http://www.gratefulweb.com/articles/grateful-web-interview-leo-nocentelli|archivedate=September 25, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-nola-aug2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nola.com/voodoofest/index.ssf/2011/08/latest_meters_reunion_to_roll.html|title=Latest Meters reunion to roll on at least through Voodoo Fest|author=Keith Spera|publisher=nola.com|date=August 17, 2011|accessdate=October 10, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809022614/http://www.nola.com/voodoofest/index.ssf/2011/08/latest_meters_reunion_to_roll.html|archivedate=August 9, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-dvd-release\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/movie/pid/6393747/a/rock+house+method:&frm=www.cduniverse.com|title=Rock House Method: The Secrets of Funk Guitar DVD|publisher=cduniverse.com|accessdate=October 14, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20171014154345/https://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/movie/pid/6393747/a/rock+house+method:&frm=www.cduniverse.com|archivedate=October 14, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-rhythm-EP\">{{cite web|url=http://neworleansmusiconline.com/wordpress/?p=29|title=New Release from Meters Guitarist Leo Nocentelli|publisher=New Orleans Music Online|date=May 29, 2009|accessdate=October 17, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090616125126/http://neworleansmusiconline.com/wordpress/?p=29|archivedate=June 16, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-offbeat-art-george\">{{cite web|url=http://www.offbeat.com/articles/meter-men-an-offbeat-interview-with-art-neville-and-george-porter-jr/|title=Meter Men: An OffBeat Interview with Art Neville and George Porter, Jr.|publisher=OffBeat magazine|date=May 1, 1995|accessdate=October 21, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141207130937/http://www.offbeat.com/articles/meter-men-an-offbeat-interview-with-art-neville-and-george-porter-jr/|archivedate=December 7, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-lifetime-grammy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/tina-turner-queen-2018-recording-academy-special-merit-awards|title=Tina Turner To Queen: 2018 Recording Academy Special Merit Awards|publisher=grammy.com|author=Ren\u00e9e Fabian|date=January 9, 2018|accessdate=August 10, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407155511/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/tina-turner-queen-2018-recording-academy-special-merit-awards|archivedate=April 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YMItAAAAYAAJ|title=Up from the Cradle of Jazz|author1=Jason Berry|author2= Jonathan Foose|author3=Tad Jones|publisher=Da Capo Press|year=1992|isbn=9780306804939|pages=190\u2013200}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/musicalgumbomusi00lich|url-access=registration|title=Musical Gumbo: The Music of New Orleans|author1=Grace Lichtenstein|author2=Laura Dankner|publisher=W.W. Norton|year=1993|isbn=9780393034684|pages=[https://archive.org/details/musicalgumbomusi00lich/page/153 153]\u2013160}}\n\n==External Links==\n* [https://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/leo-nocentelli Leo Nocentelli Interview] NAMM Oral History Library (2020)\n\n{{The Meters}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nocentelli, Leo}}\n[[Category:American funk guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American session musicians]]\n[[Category:American soul guitarists]]\n[[Category:African-American songwriters]]\n[[Category:African-American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Rhythm and blues musicians from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Louisiana Creole people]]\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The Meters members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American musician and songwriter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Leo Nocentelli\n| image = Leo-Nocentelli-new-york-city-august-3-2006.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption = Nocentelli performing in 2006\n| background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1946|6|15}}<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" />\n| birth_place = [[New Orleans, Louisiana]]\n| instrument = Guitar\n| label = \n| genre = [[Funk]], [[R&B]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[Rock music|rock]], [[jazz]]\n| occupation = Musician, songwriter\n| years_active = Late 1950s\u2013present\n| associated_acts = {{nowrap|[[The Meters]]}}, {{nowrap|Neville Sounds}}, {{nowrap|The Funky Meters}}, {{nowrap|The Meter Men}}\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Leo Nocentelli''' (born June 15, 1946) is an American musician and songwriter best known as a founding member and lead guitarist of the [[funk]] band [[The Meters]]. He wrote the original versions of several funk classics such as \"[[Cissy Strut]]\" and \"Hey Pocky A-Way\". As a session musician he has recorded with a variety of notable artists such as [[Dr. John]], [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]] and [[Etta James]]. He is the recipient of a Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award as a member of The Meters.\n\n==Career==\n\nNocentelli grew up in the [[Irish Channel, New Orleans|Irish Channel]] and [[Seventh Ward, New Orleans|Seventh Ward]] neighborhoods of New Orleans. He was encouraged by his father to pursue music. He played [[ukulele]] at an early age and started on guitar at age twelve.<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /><ref name=\"ln-louisiana music\" /> He gravitated to jazz and was influenced by jazz guitarists [[Charlie Christian]], [[Barney Kessel]], [[Johnny Smith]] and [[Kenny Burrell]].<ref name=\"ln-allmusic-bio\" /> His first professional gig was at age thirteen.<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /> By age fourteen he was backing notable musicians such as [[Otis Redding]] and [[Clyde McPhatter]].<ref name=\"ln-louisiana music\" /> He played jazz, [[Dixieland]], [[rhythm and blues]], and [[Rock and roll|rock]].<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2011\" />{{rp|page=2}} He joined the [[The Hawketts|Hawketts]] and developed a reputation as a guitarist. At age seventeen he did session work for Motown acts including the [[The Supremes|Supremes]], [[The Temptations|Temptations]], and [[The Spinners (American R&B group)|Spinners]].<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /><ref name=\"ln-musical gumbo\" />\n\nIn 1964 he was drafted and served in the army for two years. During [[Leave (U.S. military)|leaves]] he did session work in New Orleans. After the service he joined Art Neville and the Neville Sounds, at the time a recently founded seven-piece band. By 1968 the band consisted of four members: Nocentelli, [[Art Neville]], [[George Porter Jr.|George Porter]], and [[Ziggy Modeliste]].<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /> The band had a fluid style and each instrument was free to go anywhere musically.<ref name=\"ln-louisiana music\" /> The band performed dance-style rhythm and blues at the Ivanhoe nightclub six nights a week. On Sundays, Nocentelli, Porter, and Modeliste performed jazz gigs.<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /><ref name=\"ln-musical gumbo\" /> Nocentelli said his bandmates were his biggest influence and called his experience up to this point in time the learning phase of his career.<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2004\" /><ref name=\"ln-blues blog\" />\n\nThe band released two singles as [[The Meters]], \"Sophisticated Cissy\" and \"[[Cissy Strut]]\", both originally written by Nocentelli.<ref name=\"ln-hotg-singles-2011\" /><ref name=\"ln-vintage2002\" /> The commercial success of \"Cissy Strut\" became an impetus for the band's subsequent recording career as The Meters.<ref name=\"ln-vintage2002\" /> From 1969 to 1977 the band released eight studio albums, with Nocentelli as one of the primary songwriters.<ref name=\"ln-zig2008\" /> He wrote the original versions of funk songs such as \"People Say\" and \"Hey Pocky A-Way\".<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2004\" /><ref name=\"ln-gibson-2010\" /> Early on, improvisation was a major part of song development.<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2012\" />{{rp|page=2}} Though the band gained notoriety in the music community, the lack of commercial success along with managerial and artistic factors gave way to their disbandment in late 1970s.<ref name=\"ln-am-meters-bio\" /><ref name=\"ln-musical gumbo\" />\n\nThroughout the 1960s and 1970s, Nocentelli wrote, co-wrote and did session work \u2013 mostly in [[Cosimo Matassa|Cosimo]], [[Allen Toussaint#Sansu: Soul and early New Orleans funk|Sansu]], and [[Sea-Saint Studios|Sea-Saint]] studios.<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /><ref name=\"ln-allmusic-bio\" /><ref name=\"ln-jambands-2004\" /><ref name=\"ln-sundazed-2002\" /> As songwriter and producer, he learned from and was influenced by [[Allen Toussaint]].<ref name=\"ln-westword-2009\" /><ref name=\"ln-nola-dec2015\" /> He backed a variety of artists such as [[Dr. John]], [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]], [[Albert King]], [[Etta James]], [[Joe Cocker]], [[Earl King]], [[Chris Kenner]], and [[Betty Harris]].<ref name=\"ln-sundazed-2002\" /><ref name=\"ln-allmusic-bio\" /><ref name=\"ln-jambands-2004\" />\n\nIn the early 1980s Nocentelli toured with [[Jimmy Buffett]]. He moved to Los Angeles in 1982.<ref name=\"ln-nola-dec2015\" /> He continued to do session work and performed regularly with former bandmate George Porter as GEO/LEO.<ref name=\"ln-vintage2002\" /><ref name=\"ln-gibson-2010\" /> He also remained close with Modeliste, who had moved to the [[San Francisco Bay Area]]. They performed in various quartet formations and released a live album titled ''[[Nocentelli: Live in San Francisco]]''.<ref name=\"ln-offbeat-may2015\" /><ref name=\"ln-blues-access\" /> At one of their shows in 1989, Nocentelli and Porter invited Modeliste and Neville on stage. The impromptu performance was the first reunion of the original Meters.<ref name=\"ln-vintage2002\" /> The same year Nocentelli, Neville, and Porter formed The Funky Meters with [[Russell Batiste Jr.|Russell Batiste]] on drums. Nocentelli performed with the reincarnated lineup until 1993.<ref name=\"ln-funk-third ear\" />\n\nHe briefly moved back to New Orleans in the early 1990s and returned to Los Angeles in 1992.<ref name=\"ln-offbeat-may2015\" /> He continued to perform with two Meters-inspired lineups: The Meter Men and The Meters Experience. The Meter Men are Nocentelli, Porter, and Modeliste with [[Page McConnell]] on keyboards; variations included keyboardists [[Galactic|Rich Vogel]], [[Papa Grows Funk|John Gros]], and drummer Russell Batiste.<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2012\" /><ref name=\"ln-nola2015perform\" /> The Meters Experience is Nocentelli in various quartets with [[Bernie Worrell]], [[Bill Dickens]], [[Oteil Burbridge]], [[Al Di Meola]], [[God Street Wine|Jason Crosby]], George Laks, Albert Margolis, Jamal Batiste, Ricky Cortez, Felix Pollard, and others.<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2011\" /><ref name=\"ln-gibson-2010\" /><ref name=\"ln-gratefulweb-2015\" />\n\nEarly on, Nocentelli used a [[Gibson ES-175]] hollow body guitar. He switched to a semi-hollow [[Fender Starcaster]] in mid-1970s. Around 2001 he switched to the semi-hollow [[Gibson ES-335]].<ref name=\"ln-vintage2002\" /><ref name=\"ln-sundazed-2002\" /> Nocentelli has performed in several reunions with the original Meters lineup.<ref name=\"ln-nola-aug2011\" /><ref name=\"ln-gratefulweb-2015\" /> He moved to New Orleans in 2015 and continues to perform.<ref name=\"ln-nola-dec2015\" /> He received a [[Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award]] in 2018 as a member of The Meters.<ref name=\"ln-lifetime-grammy\" />\n\n==Style==\nNocentelli was self-taught. In his early teens he emulated jazz guitarists while listening to [[phonograph records]].<ref name=\"ln-allmusic-bio\" /><ref name=\"ln-jambands-2004\" /> He was drawn to jazz, but to survive professionally he had to become proficient in multiple genres.<ref name=\"ln-allmusic-bio\" /><ref name=\"ln-jambands-2011\" /> In 1960s and 1970s he was part of an era in which New Orleans jazz gave way to rhythm and blues, and funk.<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /><ref>Berry 1992, ''Up from the Cradle of Jazz'', pp. 16, 192, 196.</ref> Nocentelli's band, The Meters, were innovative and set the stylistic tone of [[Funk#History|New Orleans funk]].<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\" /><ref name=\"ln-am-meters-bio\" /> The band's early works were rooted in improvisation.<ref name=\"ln-jambands-2012\" /><ref name=\"ln-offbeat-art-george\" /> According to Nocentelli, genres are relative and he alludes to incorporating different genres in his style.<ref name=\"ln-blues blog\" /><ref name=\"ln-jambands-2011\" /> He said in funk as well as in [[rhythm guitar]] you have to complement and react to what you hear, and said that is not a teachable skill.<ref name=\"ln-gibson-2010\" /> In addition to live performance and session work, songwriting was a significant part of Nocentelli's contribution.<ref name=\"ln-zig2008\" /><ref name=\"ln-vintage2002\" />\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|The Meters#Discography}}\n\n===As leader===\n* ''[[Nocentelli: Live in San Francisco]]'' ([[DJM Records|DJM]], 1997)\n* ''Rhythm & Rhymes Part 1'' (TLB, 2009)<ref name=\"ln-rhythm-EP\" />\n* ''The Secrets of Funk: Using it and Fusing it !'' (2003) \u2013 instructional DVD<ref name=\"ln-dvd-release\" />\n\n===With others===\nCredits partly adapted from [[AllMusic]].<ref name=\"ln-am-bio-credits\" />\n{{Expand list|date=March 2016}}\n\n* ''[[Nightbirds]]'' ([[Epic Records|Epic]], 1974) with [[Labelle]]\n* ''[[Sneakin' Sally Through the Alley]]'' ([[Island Records|Island]], 1974) with [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]]\n* ''[[The Wild Tchoupitoulas (album)|The Wild Tchoupitoulas]]'' ([[Mango Records|Mango]], 1976) with [[The Wild Tchoupitoulas]]\n* ''[[Patti LaBelle (album)|Patti LaBelle]]'' (Epic, 1977) with [[Patti LaBelle]]\n* ''[[Changes (Etta James album)|Changes]]'' ([[MCA Records|MCA]], 1980) with [[Etta James]]\n* ''[[On the Line (Michael Wycoff album)|On the Line]]'' ([[RCA Records|RCA]], 1983) with [[Michael Wycoff]] \n* ''Let My People Go'' ([[Qwest Records|Quest]], 1985) with [[The Winans]]\n* ''[[Winner in You]]'' (MCA, 1986) with Patti LaBelle\n* ''[[Tenderness (Kip Hanrahan album)|Tenderness]]'' (American Clave, 1990) with [[Kip Hanrahan]]\n* ''[[Storyville (album)|Storyville]]'' ([[Geffen Records|Geffen]], 1991) with [[Robbie Robertson]]\n* ''[[Us (Peter Gabriel album)|Us]]'' (Geffen, 1992) with [[Peter Gabriel]]\n* ''Southern Exposure'' ([[Jive Records|Jive]], 1993) with [[Maceo Parker]]\n* ''Urban Blues Re: Newell'' ([[Stony Plain Records|Sony Plain]], 1995) with [[King Biscuit Boy]]\n* ''Connected'' (NYNO, 1996) with [[Allen Toussaint]]\n* ''Rock and Roll Doctor: Lowell George Tribute'' ([[CMC International|CMC]], 1997) with various artists\n* ''[[Matriarch of the Blues]]'' (Private Music, 2000) with Etta James\n* ''[[Big Wide Grin]]'' (Sony, 2001) with [[Keb' Mo']]\n* ''Sing Me Back Home'' ([[Sony BMG]], 2006) with New Orleans Social Club<ref name=\"ln-am-review-singhome\" />\n* ''Unlock Your Mind'' ([[Rounder Records|Rounder]], 2012) with [[The Soul Rebels]]\n* ''Parking Lot Symphony'' ([[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]], 2017) with [[Trombone Shorty]]\n\n==External Links==\n* [https://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/leo-nocentelli Leo Nocentelli Interview] NAMM Oral History Library (2020)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"ln-cradle-1992\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YMItAAAAYAAJ|title=Up from the Cradle of Jazz|author1=Jason Berry|author2= Jonathan Foose|author3=Tad Jones|publisher=Da Capo Press|year=1992|accessdate=November 17, 2015|isbn=9780306804939|pages=190\u2013200}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ln-allmusic-bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/leo-nocentelli-mn0000975844/biography|title=Allmusic: Leo Nocentelli \u2013 biography|publisher=Allmusic.com|accessdate=November 12, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505230138/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/leo-nocentelli-mn0000975844/biography|archivedate=May 5, 2016|url-status